trip:
  name: Japan — May to July 2026
  author: Bruna Sanches Caricati & Renan Cammarosano de Lima
  duration: 59 nights
  tags: [japan, asia, first-time, culture, history, food, onsen, temples]
  info:
  - ANA-reservation: F7ZHBA
  - ANA-ticket: 2052429593670-671
  note: |
    A two-month journey through Japan — Tokyo, Hakone, Osaka, Hiroshima,
    Kyoto, and back to Tokyo. First visit for both. Focus on history, culture,
    and authentic food. No seafood preference — prioritise meat, tofu, and
    vegetable options when ordering.

    **Rainy season (tsuyu) warning:** Most of the long Tokyo stay (June 6 –
    July 3) falls inside Japan's rainy season. Expect intermittent showers
    and high humidity (22–28C / 70–90% humidity). It does not rain all day —
    roughly 40–50% chance on any given day. Plan outdoor activities for
    mornings; keep museums and indoor experiences for afternoons.
    Rainy Kyoto temples and gardens are often the most atmospheric.

    **Grutto Pass:** Buy on arrival in Tokyo long stay (June 6, from any
    participating venue). Valid for 2 months at 107 museums, gardens, and
    zoos. Essential for the 27-night Tokyo stay. Cost: 2,500 yen.

    **Luggage forwarding (TA-Q-BIN):** Use Yamato Transport's luggage
    forwarding service between every hotel change. Send bags the night
    before you travel — they arrive the next day (1,500–2,500 yen per bag).
    Eliminates hauling suitcases through train stations entirely.

    **Apps to install before departure:**
    Suica (Apple Pay / IC card), Google Maps offline, Tabelog (restaurants),
    Smart EX (Shinkansen bookings), Visit Japan Web (immigration forms),
    EMot (Hakone Freepass and Romancecar tickets already here),
    GetYourGuide (Skytree and teamLab tickets live here).

    **Money:** Withdraw yen at 7-Eleven or Japan Post ATMs — most reliable
    for foreign cards. Many small restaurants and neighbourhood shops are
    still cash-only. Start with 30,000–50,000 yen in cash on arrival.

    **JR Pass:** Not recommended for this trip. Only 5 major Shinkansen
    legs total. Individual tickets via Smart EX are significantly cheaper.

itinerary:

  # ──────────────────────────────────────────
  # OUTBOUND FLIGHTS
  # ──────────────────────────────────────────

- flight:
    from:
      name: Palma de Mallorca Airport (PMI)
      lat: 39.5517
      lng: 2.7388
    to:
      name: Zurich Airport (ZRH)
      lat: 47.4647
      lng: 8.5492
    departs: 2026-05-04T08:20
    arrives: 2026-05-04T10:15
    info:
    - operator: Eurowings
    - flight: EW6836
    - seat: 20B
    - class: W
    - reservation: F7ZHBA

- flight:
    from:
      name: Zurich Airport (ZRH)
    to:
      name: Tokyo Narita International Airport (NRT)
      lat: 35.7647
      lng: 140.3864
    departs: 2026-05-04T13:05
    arrives: 2026-05-05T09:10
    info:
    - operator: ANA (operated by Swiss)
    - flight: NH6752
    - class: Q
    - reservation: F7ZHBA
    note: |
      Fill in Visit Japan Web forms before landing to speed through
      immigration. Try to sleep on the plane — Japan is 7 time zones
      ahead of Spain.

  # ──────────────────────────────────────────
  # TOKYO — WEEK ONE (7 nights)
  # ──────────────────────────────────────────

- Tokyo:
    arrives: 2026-05-05
    departs: 2026-05-12
    duration: 7 nights
    location: Tokyo, Japan
    stay:
    - Sakura Hotel Nippori:
        arrives: 2026-05-05T15:00
        departs: 2026-05-12T11:00
        location:
          address: Sendagi 3-43-15, Bunkyo Ward, Tokyo 113-0022, Japan
          lat: 35.7283
          lng: 139.7614
        info:
        - confirmation: "5531.957.709"
        - pin: "4587"
        - phone: +81 3 5685 1200
        - platform: Booking.com
        - room: Japanese-Style Room with Shared Bathroom (futon, tatami)
        - cancellation: free until May 3
        - price: approx. 84,823 yen — pay at property
        note: |
          Yanaka-Sendagi is one of Tokyo's best-preserved old
          neighbourhoods. From Narita take the Keisei Skyliner to
          Nippori Station (41 min, 2,570 yen) — direct and easiest.
          Purchase a Suica card at the airport before boarding.

    activities:

    - day:
        title: Arrival day — easy does it
        time: 2026-05-05
        note: |
          You have crossed 7 time zones. The goal today is arrival,
          a first meal, a slow walk, and an early night. Resist
          the urge to overdo it.
        items:
        - Arrive Narita and transfer to hotel:
            time: morning
            note: |
              Take the Keisei Skyliner from Narita T1/T2 to Nippori
              (41 min, 2,570 yen). Check in from 3pm — if early,
              leave bags and head straight out.
        - Yanaka Cemetery:
            time: afternoon
            duration: 1h
            tags: [walk, history, atmosphere]
            location:
              name: Yanaka Cemetery
              lat: 35.7260
              lng: 139.7658
            note: |
              A vast Edo-period cemetery where the city's great and
              ordinary rest together — moss-covered stone lanterns,
              ancient camphor trees, and an overwhelming quiet that
              feels miles from the capital.

              **Cultural note:** Yanaka survived the 1923 earthquake and the 1945
              firebombing, making it one of the only places in Tokyo
              where Edo-era street patterns still exist. Japanese
              cemeteries are not places of avoidance — families
              picnic under cherry trees here in spring. Walking
              through Yanaka Cemetery feels like a genuine break in time.
        - Yanaka Ginza:
            time: late afternoon
            duration: 45m
            tags: [traditional street, neighbourhood, food]
            location:
              name: Yanaka Ginza
              lat: 35.7243
              lng: 139.7670
            note: |
              Try the menchi katsu (deep-fried meat patty) sold hot from the butchers.

              A 170m covered shopping street of old Tokyo — local
              butchers, sembei (rice cracker) shops, tofu sellers,
              and small cafes, most run by the same families for
              generations.

              **Cultural note:** This is what the shitamachi (working-class downtown)
              looked and felt like before Tokyo was rebuilt. The
              difference between Yanaka Ginza and any tourist shopping
              street is that the people here are buying their dinner,
              not souvenirs.


        - Nezu Shrine:
            time: late afternoon
            tags: [shrine, nature, cultural]
            location:
              name: Nezu Shrine
              lat: 35.7197
              lng: 139.7619
            note: |
              A rare intact Edo-period shrine in central Tokyo, with
              a small tunnel of red torii gates climbing the wooded
              hill behind the main sanctuary.

              **Cultural note:** Established by the fifth shogun Tsunayoshi in 1706,
              the site has been sacred far longer. Unlike Fushimi
              Inari, this torii tunnel is intimate and almost always
              quiet — a genuine discovery a few minutes from the hotel.
        - Local izakaya dinner:
            time: evening
            tags: [food, neighbourhood]
            note: |
              Ask the hotel for a neighbourhood izakaya recommendation.
              Order yakitori (grilled chicken skewers), edamame,
              gyoza, and karaage (fried chicken). Have one drink,
              then sleep. Be in bed by 10pm.
    - day:
        title: Tsukiji market, Senso-ji, Kappabashi
        time: 2026-05-06
        note: |
          A full day in eastern Tokyo covering three historically layered
          areas. Walk most of it — the streets between destinations
          reward exploration.
        items:
        - Tsukiji Outer Market:
            time: 8am
            duration: 1h30m
            priority: must
            tags: [market, food, cultural]
            location:
              name: Tsukiji Outer Market
              lat: 35.6654
              lng: 139.7707
            note: |
              The working outer ring of what was once the world's
              largest fish market — dozens of vendors sell fresh
              produce, street food, and specialist ingredients every
              morning. Arrive by 8am for the best stalls.

              **Cultural note:** The inner wholesale market moved to Toyosu in 2018,
              but the outer vendors — many from families operating
              the same stall for four or five generations — remained.
              The egg stalls (tamagoyaki, thick sweet-savory rolled
              omelette) are exceptional even if you prefer to skip
              the seafood counters. Have breakfast here: dashimaki
              sandwiches, fresh fruit on a stick, warm tamagoyaki
              cut to order.
        - Hamarikyu Gardens:
            priority: maybe
            duration: 45m
            tags: [garden, nature, Edo period]
            location:
              name: Hamarikyu Gardens
              lat: 35.6601
              lng: 139.7634
            note: |
              A tidal garden on the bay shore, 10 minutes' walk
              from Tsukiji. Once a Tokugawa shogunate hunting ground
              and duck reserve.

              **Cultural note:** The garden's tidal pond connects to Tokyo Bay — the
              water level rises and falls with the tides. It is one
              of the only Edo-period daimyo gardens still intact in
              the city. Skip if time is tight.
        - Senso-ji Temple:
            time: 10am
            duration: 1h30m
            priority: must
            tags: [temple, cultural, landmark]
            location:
              name: Senso-ji Temple
              lat: 35.7148
              lng: 139.7967
            note: |
              Explore the side streets off Nakamise — the less touristy
              alleys around Senso-ji are where the real traditional shops
              are. The Denbo-in garden behind the main hall is a
              hidden gem when open.

              Tokyo's oldest and most visited temple — anchored by
              the great Kaminarimon (Thunder Gate) with its 700kg
              paper lantern, and the Nakamise-dori shopping street
              leading to the five-story pagoda and main hall.

              **Cultural note:** Founded 645 AD — predating the city of Tokyo by a
              thousand years. The object of worship, a golden image
              of Kannon (goddess of mercy), was reputedly pulled from
              the Sumida River by two fishermen. It has never been
              shown publicly and reportedly never will be — making
              this the most visited temple in the world for something
              no one has ever seen. The current Thunder Gate is a
              1960 postwar reconstruction funded by Panasonic's founder.

        - Kappabashi Kitchenware Street:
            time: midday
            duration: 1h
            tags: [shopping, cultural, neighbourhood]
            location:
              name: Kappabashi-dori, Taito-ku
              lat: 35.7152
              lng: 139.7865
            note: |
              A single street of over 170 professional kitchenware
              shops — knives, lacquerware, chopsticks, ceramics,
              and the incredible sampuru plastic food displays that
              fill restaurant windows across Japan.

              **Cultural note:** Sampuru (food replicas) were invented here in the 1930s,
              originally made from wax. The industry was born from
              a desire to help customers understand menus without
              pointing at pictures (considered awkward). Today the
              most detailed pieces take artisans days to make. Good
              place to buy a quality Japanese knife (cheaper than
              dedicated knife shops) or a proper set of chopsticks.
        - Hoppy Street and Asakusa backstreets:
            time: late afternoon
            duration: 1h
            tags: [walk, neighbourhood, food]
            note: |
              The quiet lanes east of Nakamise toward Hoppy Street
              — old-school izakayas popular with local salarymen,
              a good spot for a late afternoon drink and small plates.
        - Tempura dinner in Asakusa:
            time: evening
            tags: [food, local specialty]
            note: |
              Asakusa is Tokyo's historic centre of tempura.
              Daikokuya (est. 1887) is the neighbourhood institution
              — arrive before 6pm to avoid a queue, or try the
              smaller places on the side streets east of Nakamise.

              **Cultural note:** Tempura was introduced by Portuguese missionaries in
              the 16th century — the word derives from Latin. Tokyo-
              style (Edo-mae) tempura uses sesame oil and is served
              with a light tentsuyu broth, distinct from Kyoto or
              Osaka styles. Order the kakiage (mixed vegetable and
              batter cake) alongside regular pieces.
    - day:
        title: Ueno and Akihabara, then Skytree and teamLab
        time: 2026-05-07
        note: |
          Two fixed tickets this evening — Skytree at 6pm and teamLab
          at 7:30pm. The transit between them takes 25–30 minutes.
          Leave Akihabara no later than 5:15pm.
        items:
        - Tokyo National Museum:
            time: 9am
            duration: 2h30m
            priority: must
            tags: [museum, history, culture]
            location:
              name: Tokyo National Museum
              lat: 35.7189
              lng: 139.7764
            note: |
              Japan's oldest and largest museum — the Honkan gallery
              alone holds samurai armour, lacquerware, woodblock
              prints, Buddhist sculpture, and ceramics spanning
              12 centuries of Japanese civilisation.

              **Cultural note:** Founded 1872, one year after the Meiji government
              abolished the feudal system. The Horyuji Treasures
              Gallery (a separate building) holds Buddhist objects
              from 607 AD — one of the finest rooms of Asian art
              anywhere in the world. Do not skip it. Focus on the
              Honkan and the Horyuji building; return for the
              Heiseikan during the long Tokyo stay.
        - Shinobazu Pond and Ueno Park:
            time: 11:30am
            duration: 30m
            tags: [nature, park, walk]
            location:
              name: Shinobazu Pond, Ueno
              lat: 35.7131
              lng: 139.7714
            note: |
              A large lotus pond in the middle of Ueno Park, with a
              small Benten shrine on an island accessed by a narrow
              causeway. In summer the lotus flowers are spectacular.

              **Cultural note:** Benten (Benzaiten) is the goddess of everything that
              flows — water, music, time, words, eloquence. Her
              shrines are almost always on islands or peninsulas.
              This one was built in 1625 for the third shogun Iemitsu.
        - Ameyoko Market (lunch):
            time: midday
            duration: 45m
            tags: [market, food, walk]
            location:
              name: Ameyoko Market, Ueno
              lat: 35.7089
              lng: 139.7745
            note: |
              A chaotic covered market running under the JR elevated
              tracks — fruit sellers, cheap clothing, dried goods,
              and dozens of street food stalls. Walk and eat.

              **Cultural note:** "Ame" means both candy and America — the market grew
              from a postwar black market selling American goods
              during the occupation (1945-1952). The military surplus
              and nylon stockings have given way to haggling vendors
              and tourist snacks, but the market retains its
              compressed, slightly chaotic energy.
        - Akihabara Electric Town:
            time: 1:30pm
            duration: 2h
            tags: [electronics, pop culture, cultural]
            location:
              name: Akihabara Electric Town
              lat: 35.7022
              lng: 139.7742
            note: |
              Tokyo's electronics and anime district — multi-floor
              shops stacked with retro game cartridges, figurines,
              trading cards, and consumer electronics, with maid
              cafes and arcades throughout.

              **Cultural note:** Akihabara was an electrical components district after
              WWII, evolved into consumer electronics, then anime
              and gaming in the 1980s and 1990s. The otaku (obsessive
              fan) culture that coalesced here is now one of Japan's
              major cultural exports. Yodobashi Camera (7 floors)
              is worth a slow exploration.
        - Travel to Oshiage:
            time: 5:15pm
            tags: [logistics]
            note: |
              Toei Asakusa Line from Asakusa toward Oshiage, 2 stops.
              Total: about 20 minutes. Allow extra time.

        - Tokyo Skytree — Tembo Deck:
            time: 6pm
            priority: must
            duration: 50m
            tags: [viewpoint, landmark]
            location:
              name: Tokyo Skytree
              lat: 35.7101
              lng: 139.8107
            info:
            - booking: GYGBLHRMGF63 (GetYourGuide app)
            - price: 19.54 EUR for 2 adults
            note: |
              The world's second-tallest tower at 634 metres. The
              Tembo Deck at 350 metres gives a 360° panorama of
              Tokyo — on clear days, Mount Fuji appears to the west.

              **Cultural note:** 634 metres was chosen deliberately — in old Japanese
              the number reads as "musashi" (6-3-4), the ancient
              name for the Kanto region. The tower replaced Tokyo
              Tower as the city's broadcast antenna when the switch
              to digital TV required greater height. Leave by 6:55pm
              for the transit to teamLab.
        - Transit to teamLab Planets (Toyosu):
            time: 7pm
            duration: 25m
            tags: [logistics]
            note: |
              From Oshiage: Toei Asakusa Line to Higashi-Ginza,
              then Yurakucho Line 2 stops to Toyosu. Allow 25-30
              minutes. If unsure, take a taxi (2,000-3,000 yen,
              about 20 min).

        - teamLab Planets TOKYO:
            time: 7:30pm
            priority: must
            duration: 1h30m
            tags: [art, immersive, experience]
            location:
              name: teamLab Planets TOKYO
              lat: 35.6500
              lng: 139.7847
            info:
            - booking: GYG9966Q2V24 (GetYourGuide app)
            - price: 49.92 EUR for 2 adults
            note: |
              Four large-scale immersive art environments — including
              a room where you wade barefoot through ankle-deep water
              as projected koi scatter when you step, and a garden
              of flowers in infinite bloom.

              **Cultural note:** teamLab's art philosophy is rooted in the Japanese
              concept of "ma" — the meaningful space between things.
              The water room works because you cannot pass through
              it without affecting it. Bring shorts or clothes you
              don't mind getting slightly damp. No shoes inside.
    - day:
        title: Odaiba by monorail, Shibuya at dusk
        time: 2026-05-08
        items:
        - Yurikamome monorail to Odaiba:
            time: 10am
            tags: [transport, experience]
            note: |
              Sit at the very front — the crossing over the bay is the point.

              A driverless elevated monorail from Shimbashi curving
              out over Tokyo Bay, crossing the Rainbow Bridge before
              arriving at Odaiba's waterfront.


        - Gundam statue and DiverCity:
            time: 10:30am
            duration: 1h
            tags: [pop culture, experience]
            location:
              name: DiverCity Tokyo Plaza
              lat: 35.6249
              lng: 139.7756
            note: |
              A life-size Gundam mobile suit stands in front of the
              DiverCity mall — periodically lights up and moves.
              The Gundam Base inside sells every scale of model kit.

              **Cultural note:** Gundam (1979) is to Japan what Star Wars is to the West
              — a defining sci-fi franchise that shaped a generation's
              aesthetics and philosophy. The model kit industry
              generates billions of yen annually. Even with no knowledge
              of the franchise, the scale of the outdoor installation
              is impressive.
        - Odaiba beach and waterfront:
            duration: 45m
            tags: [nature, walk, scenic]
            note: |
              A sandy beach on Tokyo Bay with clear views of the
              Rainbow Bridge and the city towers rising behind it.

              **Cultural note:** Odaiba was built on artificial islands originally
              constructed in 1853 as defensive gun batteries after
              Commodore Perry's Black Ships arrived and the shogunate
              realised Japan had no coastal defences. Only three of
              the planned eleven fortresses were ever completed.
        - Shibuya Crossing at dusk:
            time: 5:30pm
            priority: must
            duration: 45m
            tags: [landmark, cultural, experience]
            location:
              name: Shibuya Scramble Crossing
              lat: 35.6595
              lng: 139.7004
            note: |
              Watch from Shibuya Sky (open rooftop, 2,000 yen — book
              online in advance), or the 2F Starbucks Tsutaya window.
              Then cross it yourself. Dinner in Shibuya or Daikanyama.

              The world's busiest pedestrian crossing — at peak hours
              up to 2,500 people cross simultaneously from all
              directions as neon signs ignite across five towers above.

              **Cultural note:** The scramble system (all signals red simultaneously,
              allowing pedestrians to cross in every direction) was
              implemented to reduce accidents at an intersection too
              busy to manage conventionally. It is now a globally
              recognised image of urban Japan — density, order within
              apparent chaos, and the indifference of each individual
              to the spectacle they collectively create.

    - day:
        title: Shinjuku — gardens, government building, nightlife
        time: 2026-05-09
        items:
        - Shinjuku Gyoen National Garden:
            time: 9am
            duration: 2h
            priority: must
            tags: [garden, nature, tranquil]
            location:
              name: Shinjuku Gyoen
              lat: 35.6852
              lng: 139.7101
            note: |
              58 hectares of formal gardens on the grounds of a former
              imperial estate — a French formal garden, an English
              landscape garden, and a Japanese strolling garden
              coexist within the same walls. One of Tokyo's most
              peaceful spaces. Entry 500 yen.

              **Cultural note:** Originally an agricultural research farm for the Meiji
              imperial household (1879), then an imperial retreat.
              Public since 1949. The no-alcohol rule — unusual in
              Japan's permissive park culture — was introduced
              specifically to prevent it becoming a rowdy cherry
              blossom party venue.
        - Tokyo Metropolitan Government Building:
            time: 11:30am
            duration: 45m
            tags: [viewpoint, free, architecture]
            location:
              name: Tokyo Metropolitan Government Building
              lat: 35.6895
              lng: 139.6917
            note: |
              Free observation deck on the 45th floor of city hall
              — 360° views of the Shinjuku skyline and on clear days
              Mount Fuji visible to the west. Designed by Kenzo Tange.

              **Cultural note:** Tange's facades were inspired by Notre-Dame Cathedral's
              Gothic towers — he wanted to suggest that a democratic
              city hall could carry the same civic authority as a
              medieval cathedral. The free observation deck is
              intentionally democratic: the view belongs to the city.
        - Takashimaya Times Square depachika (lunch):
            time: midday
            tags: [food, cultural, experience]
            note: |
              The B1-B2 basement floors of the Takashimaya department
              store — one of Japan's finest depachika (department
              store food halls), with prepared dishes, premium
              wagashi sweets, sake, and bento boxes from restaurant
              kitchens.

              **Cultural note:** The depachika is a distinctly Japanese institution —
              in Japan's gift-giving culture where omiyage are brought
              back from every trip, premium food packaging is an art
              form. Walk both floors before deciding what to eat;
              grazing several counters is entirely acceptable.
        - Kabukicho and east Shinjuku:
            time: 2pm
            duration: 1h30m
            tags: [neighbourhood, cultural, urban]
            note: |
              Tokyo's entertainment quarter — a dense grid of karaoke
              bars, cinemas, pachinko parlours, live music venues,
              anchored by the Tokyu Kabukicho Tower and the famous
              Godzilla head on the Toho Building roof.

              **Cultural note:** Kabukicho was planned post-WWII as a culture district
              (a kabuki theatre never built gave it its name). It
              evolved organically into Tokyo's main entertainment
              zone — simultaneously seedy and vibrant, overwhelming
              and perfectly safe to walk through in the afternoon.
        - Omoide Yokocho (Memory Lane):
            time: 6pm
            priority: must
            duration: 1h
            tags: [food, atmosphere, cultural]
            location:
              name: Omoide Yokocho
              lat: 35.6939
              lng: 139.7006
            note: |
              A narrow alley of tiny yakitori stalls under the
              Shinjuku train tracks — each fits 8-10 people, smoke
              rising from charcoal grills, paper lanterns swinging.

              **Cultural note:** Omoide Yokocho grew from the black market under the
              train tracks after WWII, when charcoal-grilled chicken
              offcuts were affordable food for workers rebuilding the
              city. Many stalls are run by the grandchildren of those
              original vendors. Order negima (chicken and spring
              onion), kawa (skin), tsukune (minced patty). Have one
              or two skewers — this is atmosphere more than a meal.
        - Golden Gai:
            time: 7:30pm
            priority: must
            duration: 1h30m
            tags: [nightlife, cultural, bar]
            location:
              name: Golden Gai
              lat: 35.6943
              lng: 139.7035
            note: |
              Six narrow alleys containing roughly 200 tiny bars,
              each with its own personality fitting no more than
              6-8 customers — horror movie bars, jazz bars, bars
              themed around cats, bars with no theme at all.

              **Cultural note:** The land has been under development threat since the
              1960s. The bar owners collectively resisted every
              demolition attempt, some violently in the 1980s when
              the yakuza attempted forced acquisition. What survived
              is one of the world's last examples of post-WWII bar
              alley culture. Walk the lanes first, find a bar whose
              vibe you like, duck in. Foreigners are welcome.
    - day:
        title: Day trip — Mount Takao
        time: 2026-05-10
        note: |
          Leave by 8am. Keio Line from Shinjuku to Takaosanguchi
          Station (45 min, ~400 yen each). One of Japan's most climbed
          mountains — don't let that suggest it feels crowded.
        items:
        - Mount Takao — Trail 1:
            priority: must
            duration: 4h
            tags: [hiking, nature, temple, Shingo Buddhism]
            location:
              name: Mount Takao
              lat: 35.6256
              lng: 139.2434
            note: |
              Trail 1 (3.8km, 1.5h uphill) is the main paved path
              with the temple halfway. Return via Trail 4 — it
              crosses a suspension bridge through deep cedar forest
              and is quieter. Take the cable car (490 yen) down
              if tired. Eat dango (grilled rice dumplings) at the
              summit stalls. Check fuji-san.info in the morning
              for Fuji visibility — May is one of the best months.

              A 599m mountain on Tokyo's western edge, covered in
              ancient cedar forest, with Trail 1 passing through
              the atmospheric Yakuo-in temple complex halfway up
              before emerging at the summit with views of the Kanto
              plain and Mount Fuji on clear days.

              **Cultural note:** Yakuo-in Temple (744 AD, Shingon Buddhism) is one of
              Japan's three great Tengu temples. The tengu (mountain
              spirits, half-human half-bird) are believed to inhabit
              these peaks, and their statues line the approach to
              the main hall. The fire-walking ceremony (Hiwatari
              Matsuri) held each March draws pilgrims who walk
              barefoot across burning coals as an act of purification.
              Climbing this mountain has been a religious act for
              1,300 years.

    - day:
        title: Meiji Shrine at dawn, Harajuku, Omotesando, Shibuya Sky
        time: 2026-05-11
        items:
        - Meiji Jingu Shrine:
            time: 7:30am
            priority: must
            duration: 1h30m
            tags: [shrine, nature, spiritual]
            location:
              name: Meiji Jingu Shrine
              lat: 35.6763
              lng: 139.6993
            note: |
              Arrive at 7:30am. The inner garden (irises in bloom
              in May) costs 500 yen and is deeply worth it.

              A Shinto shrine set within 70 hectares of forested
              grounds in the heart of the city — the 700m forested
              approach of zelkova and camphor trees is extraordinary
              at dawn, before tour groups arrive.

              **Cultural note:** Built 1920 to honour Emperor Meiji (1852-1912) and
              Empress Shoken — the rulers who oversaw Japan's
              transformation from feudal isolation to industrialised
              world power. The 100,000 trees were donated by people
              from across Japan and Taiwan, chosen to create a
              self-sustaining forest ecosystem designed to last
              1,000 years. On weekend mornings Shinto weddings
              process through the inner courtyard in silence.

        - Yoyogi Park:
            time: 9am
            duration: 30m
            tags: [park, nature, local]
            note: |
              54 hectares of public park adjacent to Meiji Shrine —
              open forest, wide lawns, and on weekends an
              extraordinary parade of subcultures near the west gate.

              **Cultural note:** Look for the rockabilly groups near the Harajuku Gate
              — men in elaborate 1950s American hairstyles dancing
              to early rock and roll. They have gathered here weekly
              since the early 1980s. The juxtaposition of this
              American nostalgia culture directly beside Japan's most
              sacred imperial shrine is uniquely, inexplicably Tokyo.
        - Takeshita Street, Harajuku:
            time: 10am
            duration: 1h
            tags: [youth culture, shopping, street]
            location:
              name: Takeshita Street
              lat: 35.6715
              lng: 139.7042
            note: |
              A 350m pedestrian street of youth fashion boutiques,
              crepe stands, and costume shops — the physical home
              of Harajuku fashion culture.

              **Cultural note:** Harajuku's extreme fashion culture emerged in the 1980s
              partly as acceptable rebellion against Japan's rigid
              corporate conformity. Wearing a costume in public is
              tolerated here in a way it would not be elsewhere —
              the street itself acts as a designated permission space.
              The elaborate layered crepes (French style, Japanese
              execution) were invented here and remain excellent.
        - Omotesando Avenue:
            time: 11am
            duration: 1h30m
            tags: [architecture, walk, design]
            note: |
              A tree-lined boulevard of flagship stores notable for
              their architecture — Prada (Herzog and de Meuron,
              crystal lattice facade), Tod's (Toyo Ito, tree-branching
              concrete) — world-class architects commissioned for
              retail units.

              **Cultural note:** The zelkova trees lining Omotesando were planted in
              the 1920s for the Meiji Shrine dedication and are
              legally protected. When threatened during 2020 Olympics
              preparations, a significant public campaign protected
              them. The Nezu Museum at the south end has a beautiful
              traditional garden (1,500 yen).
        - Daikanyama and T-Site Tsutaya:
            time: 2pm
            duration: 1h30m
            tags: [neighbourhood, bookshop, walk]
            note: |
              Tokyo's quietest sophisticated neighbourhood — a maze
              of low buildings, select shops, and excellent cafes,
              anchored by the Daikanyama T-Site Tsutaya (flagship
              bookshop and design store set in wooded grounds).

              **Cultural note:** T-Site was designed by Klein Dytham Architecture (2011)
              and is considered one of the world's most beautiful
              bookshops. The building is clad in repeating letter T
              pattern — what appears abstract is thousands of
              overlapping Ts. The shop stocks vinyl records, art
              books, and design objects alongside books.
        - Shibuya Sky — rooftop observation:
            time: 5:30pm
            priority: must
            duration: 1h
            tags: [viewpoint, experience]
            location:
              name: Shibuya Sky, Shibuya Scramble Square
              lat: 35.6590
              lng: 139.7025
            note: |
              Book online in advance (2,000 yen).

              An open-air rooftop on top of Shibuya Scramble Square
              — 360° views at the hour the city lights up and the
              Scramble Crossing below enters its peak chaos.


    - day:
        title: Light morning, then Romancecar to Hakone
        time: 2026-05-12
        items:
        - Checkout and bag handling:
            time: 11am
            note: |
              Consider TA-Q-BIN forwarding — send bags directly
              to Bansuirou Fukuzumi the night before (ryokan accepts
              from 3pm same day). Or store at Shinjuku Station
              coin lockers.

        - Shinjuku depachika browsing:
            time: 10am
            duration: 1h
            note: |
              Final Tokyo morning. Browse B1-B2 of Takashimaya or
              Odakyu. Buy a light lunch for the train, or eat at a
              standing noodle shop in the station concourse.

        - Romancecar Hakone 25:
            time: 12:20pm
            priority: must
            duration: 1h27m
            tags: [train, experience]
            location:
              name: Shinjuku Station — Odakyu Romancecar Platform
              lat: 35.6896
              lng: 139.7006
            info:
            - train: Romancecar Hakone 25
            - departs: 12:20 from Shinjuku
            - arrives: 13:47 at Hakone Yumoto
            - car: "4"
            - seats: 5D (Bruna) and 5C (Renan)
            - booking: CHS832036 (Klook)
            - price: 14.08 EUR for 2 adults
            note: |
              A premium reserved-seat express with panoramic windows,
              running direct from Shinjuku to Hakone Yumoto without
              stopping. The last 30 minutes wind through forested
              mountain river valley.

              **Cultural note:** The Romancecar (named since 1957) was designed as an
              escape train — the idea that a couple could board in
              the city and arrive somewhere deeply different in under
              90 minutes was considered romantic and modern. It still
              works. Show the Klook confirmation and Hakone Freepass
              at the platform gate.
- Hakone:
    arrives: 2026-05-12T13:47
    departs: 2026-05-14
    duration: 2 nights
    location: Hakone, Kanagawa, Japan
    tags: [onsen, nature, ryokan, mountain, volcanic, Fuji]
    stay:
    - Bansuirou Fukuzumi:
        arrives: 2026-05-12T16:00
        departs: 2026-05-14T09:00
        location:
          address: 250-0311, Hakone, Kanagawa, Japan
          lat: 35.2333
          lng: 139.1000
        info:
        - confirmation: "5549903534"
        - pin: "9274"
        - phone: 81460855531
        - platform: Booking.com
        - room: Japanese-Style Superior Room B — Private Hot Spring Bath and River View
        - price: 112,000 yen — payment scheduled May 7 (card ending 6075)
        note: |
          A ryokan with a private outdoor rotenburo (hot spring bath)
          overlooking the river. Kaiseki meals served in-room or in
          private dining. Mention seafood preference when confirming
          so the kitchen can adjust the courses.
    info:
    - Hakone-Freepass:
        first-day: 2026-05-12
        control: "2965129"
        price: 6,400 yen — already paid
        note: Verify whether second pass for Renan was purchased.
        covers: |
          Hakone Tozan Railway, Tozan Cable Car (Gora-Sounzan),
          Hakone Ropeway (Sounzan-Togendai via Owakudani),
          Lake Ashi Sightseeing Cruise, Tozan Bus, Izu-Hakone Bus.
          Does NOT cover Romancecar or Shinkansen.
        how-to-use: EMot app — www.emot-tickets.jp/my-tickets
    activities:

    - day:
        title: Arrival afternoon — Open Air Museum and first onsen
        time: 2026-05-12
        items:
        - Hakone Tozan Railway to Chokoku-no-Mori:
            time: 2pm
            tags: [train, experience]
            note: |
              Store bags at Yumoto Station coin lockers or arrange ryokan pickup first.

              Japan's steepest mountain railway, using a switchback
              system where the train reverses direction three times
              to climb the gradient. The forested hillsides are
              dense and green in May.

              **Cultural note:** The Hakone Tozan Railway (1919) was built partly to
              serve the ryokan industry. The hydrangeas planted
              along the tracks over decades bloom in mid-June into
              a wall of blue and purple visible from the windows.


        - Hakone Open-Air Museum:
            priority: must
            duration: 1h30m
            tags: [art, outdoor, sculpture]
            location:
              name: Hakone Open-Air Museum
              lat: 35.2397
              lng: 139.0472
            note: |
              A hillside museum displaying sculptures by Henry Moore,
              Rodin, Miro, Calder, and others across manicured lawn
              terraces with the Hakone mountains as backdrop. The
              Picasso Pavilion holds over 300 works.

              **Cultural note:** Japan's first outdoor museum (1969), conceived by art
              critic Kiichiro Shimizu, who believed art should exist
              in nature rather than be imprisoned in white-walled
              galleries. The outdoor footbath (ashiyu) at the museum
              is free for visitors — soak your feet in naturally
              flowing volcanic spring water while looking at sculpture.
        - Check in and first rotenburo:
            time: 4pm
            note: |
              Change into yukata (provided). Use the private rotenburo
              before dinner. This is the experience — naturally
              flowing hot spring water in a private outdoor bath above
              a mountain river, in a traditional inn. Take your time.

        - Kaiseki dinner:
            time: evening
            tags: [food, experience]
            note: |
              A multi-course seasonal meal of Kyoto-influenced Japanese
              haute cuisine — each small course beautifully presented,
              using mountain vegetables, tofu, and local ingredients.

              **Cultural note:** Kaiseki originated in the Zen tea ceremony tradition —
              light food served before a tea ceremony to prevent
              drinking matcha on an empty stomach. It evolved into
              Japan's most refined culinary form over 400 years.
    - day:
        title: The Hakone Loop — ropeway, volcano, Lake Ashi
        time: 2026-05-13
        note: |
          Do this circuit in order — it flows logically west to east,
          using each transport mode once. All legs covered by the
          Freepass. Check fuji-san.info the evening before.
        items:
        - Breakfast at the ryokan:
            time: morning
            note: Traditional Japanese breakfast — miso soup, grilled vegetables, tamagoyaki, rice, pickles. Politely 
              decline the fish if needed.

        - Tozan Railway, then cable car, then ropeway:
            time: 9am
            tags: [transport, experience]
            note: "Route: Yumoto > (Tozan) > Gora > (Cable Car) > Sounzan > (Ropeway) > Owakudani > (Ropeway continues) >
              Togendai"

        - Owakudani Volcanic Valley:
            priority: must
            duration: 45m
            tags: [nature, volcanic, experience]
            location:
              name: Owakudani
              lat: 35.2553
              lng: 139.0225
            note: |
              An active volcanic crater at 1,044m — steaming
              fumaroles, sulphur vents, boiling mud pools, and the
              famous kuro tamago (black eggs boiled in volcanic
              springs, said to add 7 years to your life).

              **Cultural note:** The valley was formed 3,000 years ago by a volcanic
              eruption of Mount Hakone. "Owakudani" means "great
              boiling valley." The eggs turn black because iron
              sulphide in the springs reacts with hydrogen sulphide
              gas coating the shell. On a clear day from here, Mount
              Fuji rises over the ridge to the north — one of the
              most dramatic views in Japan.
        - Lake Ashi Sightseeing Cruise:
            priority: must
            duration: 35m
            tags: [boat, lake, scenic]
            location:
              name: Lake Ashi (Ashino-ko)
              lat: 35.2040
              lng: 139.0260
            note: |
              A cruise across the volcanic caldera lake on one of
              the pirate-galleon-style ships, from Togendai at the
              north shore to Moto-Hakone or Hakone-machi at the south.

              **Cultural note:** Lake Ashi formed inside the caldera of Mount Hakone.
              The lake has no outflowing river — all water drains
              underground through volcanic rock. On perfectly still
              mornings, Mount Fuji's reflection appears complete in
              the water surface. The pirate ships are a tourism
              conceit from the 1960s and oddly charming.
        - Hakone Shrine:
            priority: must
            duration: 45m
            tags: [shrine, nature, cultural]
            location:
              name: Hakone Shrine
              lat: 35.1981
              lng: 139.0273
            note: |
              A Shinto shrine in ancient cedar forest at the southern
              edge of Lake Ashi — famous for its vermilion torii gate
              standing in the water, approached via a long forested
              avenue.

              **Cultural note:** Founded 757 AD by the monk Mangan. The lakeside torii
              marks the water entrance to the shrine — in the Shinto
              tradition, entering from water is the purified approach.
              Very quiet, very old. One of the most beautiful short
              walks in the Hakone area.
        - Lunch in Moto-Hakone and return by bus:
            time: midday
            note: |
              Several restaurants on the lakefront. Look for soba —
              Hakone is in buckwheat country. Return by Odakyu
              Highway Bus (Freepass) to Hakone Yumoto.

        - Final onsen and farewell kaiseki:
            time: evening
            note: |
              Last night in the ryokan. Use the private rotenburo
              again — the experience is different at night. A good
              moment to try the ryokan's sake selection.

    - day:
        title: Checkout, then to Osaka
        time: 2026-05-14
        items:
        - Breakfast and checkout:
            time: 8am
            note: Checkout 08:00-10:00. Depart for Odawara.
        - Travel to Osaka:
            note: |
              Hakone Yumoto > Odawara by Tozan train (~13 min).
              Odawara > Shin-Osaka by Nozomi Shinkansen (~1h).
              Book via Smart EX. Freepass does not cover this leg.

- train:
    from: Hakone (Odawara)
    to: Osaka (Shin-Osaka)
    note: Nozomi Shinkansen, ~1h. Book via Smart EX.

  # ──────────────────────────────────────────
  # OSAKA (4 nights)
  # ──────────────────────────────────────────

- Osaka:
    arrives: 2026-05-14
    departs: 2026-05-18
    duration: 4 nights
    location: Osaka, Japan
    tags: [city, food, castle, neighbourhood, history]
    stay:
    - "谷町君ホテル 難波80":
        arrives: 2026-05-14T15:00
        departs: 2026-05-18T10:00
        location:
          address: Naniwa-ku Ebisuhonmachi 1-9-28, Osaka 556-0013, Japan
          lat: 34.6559
          lng: 135.4986
        info:
        - confirmation: "5047.418.327"
        - pin: "6052"
        - phone: +81 6 6948 5889
        - platform: Booking.com
        - room: King Room (private hot tub, balcony, kitchen)
        - cancellation: free until May 9
        - price: approx. 50,252 yen — pay at property
    activities:

    - day:
        title: Arrival, Kuromon Market, Dotonbori
        time: 2026-05-14
        items:
        - Arrive from Hakone and check in:
            time: afternoon

        - Kuromon Ichiba Market:
            time: 4pm
            duration: 1h
            priority: must
            tags: [market, food, cultural]
            location:
              name: Kuromon Ichiba Market
              lat: 34.6667
              lng: 135.5046
            note: |
              A 580m covered market of 180+ stalls selling fresh
              produce, hot prepared foods, and specialist ingredients
              — long considered the professional kitchen of Osaka's
              restaurants.

              **Cultural note:** Kuromon Market has operated since 1902 and was originally
              a temple black market. The name comes from a nearby
              Buddhist temple's black gate. The market's vendors
              traditionally supplied Osaka's restaurant industry —
              the city's obsession with food quality (expressed in
              the concept of kuidaore: "eat until you drop") begins
              here. Go at 4pm while the food counters are still
              serving — closes around 6pm.
        - Dotonbori:
            time: 7pm
            priority: must
            duration: 2h
            tags: [landmark, food, atmosphere, night]
            location:
              name: Dotonbori Canal
              lat: 34.6687
              lng: 135.5013
            note: |
              Osaka's neon heart — a canal district of enormous
              animated signs (the running Glico man, the giant
              mechanised crab), wall-to-wall restaurants, and dense
              pedestrian energy that peaks between 7pm and midnight.

              **Cultural note:** The canal was dug in 1612 by developer Yasui Doton,
              who died before completing it. The Glico Running Man
              has been running since 1935 — the current LED version
              is the sixth. Walk the length of both canal banks,
              cross the Ebisu Bridge for photos.
        - Osaka-style okonomiyaki dinner:
            time: 7pm
            priority: must
            tags: [food, local specialty]
            note: |
              Osaka-style okonomiyaki (the original) is mixed — all
              ingredients combined into the batter rather than
              Hiroshima's layered style. Order with pork (buta),
              without seafood toppings.

              **Cultural note:** "As you like it, grilled" — okonomiyaki developed in
              Osaka as affordable street food during and after WWII
              when rice was rationed and flour was abundant. Try
              Mizuno restaurant (near Dotonbori) or any of the small
              okonomiyaki places on the surrounding side streets.
    - day:
        title: Osaka Castle, Shinsekai, Umeda Sky Building
        time: 2026-05-15
        items:
        - Osaka Castle:
            time: 9am
            priority: must
            duration: 2h
            tags: [castle, history, cultural]
            location:
              name: Osaka Castle
              lat: 34.6873
              lng: 135.5259
            note: |
              Originally the greatest castle in Japan when built in
              1583 — now an eight-story museum tower surrounded by
              enormous stone walls, wide moats, and a park of 100,000
              plum trees.

              **Cultural note:** Built by Toyotomi Hideyoshi (1537-1598), the man who
              unified Japan after a century of civil war. The castle
              was intended as a physical statement that Hideyoshi's
              power exceeded all predecessors. The current tower is
              a 1931 earthquake-proof concrete reconstruction — the
              original was burned by the Tokugawa army in 1615. The
              interior museum covers Hideyoshi's life and the Sengoku
              (Warring States) period — one of the most dramatic eras
              in Japanese history. Go early before tour groups.
        - Shinsekai and Tsutenkaku Tower:
            time: 1pm
            priority: must
            duration: 2h
            tags: [neighbourhood, cultural, viewpoint]
            location:
              name: Tsutenkaku Tower, Shinsekai
              lat: 34.6526
              lng: 135.5063
            note: |
              A retro neighbourhood built in 1912 to resemble Paris
              in the south and New York's Coney Island in the north
              — now a wonderfully weathered district of kushikatsu
              restaurants, vintage arcades, and blowfish signs.

              **Cultural note:** Tsutenkaku Tower (103m) was modelled on the Eiffel
              Tower combined with the Arc de Triomphe beneath it.
              The bronze Billiken statue inside is Osaka's unofficial
              mascot — rubbing his feet brings good luck, a belief
              so strong that his feet must be regularly repolished.
              The neighbourhood was long considered unfashionable;
              its current popularity has preserved rather than
              gentrified it, unusually.
        - Kushikatsu lunch:
            time: midday
            tags: [food, local specialty]
            note: |
              Deep-fried skewers of meat and vegetables in panko
              breadcrumbs — Osaka's other signature street food,
              eaten standing at the counter.

              **Cultural note:** Born in Shinsekai in the 1920s as cheap working-class
              food. The cardinal rule — never double-dip your skewer
              in the communal sauce — is enforced with genuine
              seriousness. Order meat and vegetable varieties.
        - Umeda Sky Building — Floating Garden Observatory:
            time: 5:30pm
            priority: must
            duration: 1h
            tags: [viewpoint, architecture]
            location:
              name: Umeda Sky Building
              lat: 34.7056
              lng: 135.4909
            note: |
              Two 40-floor towers connected at the top by a circular
              open-air observation deck — viewed from below it
              resembles a triumphal arch for the future. Best at sunset.

              **Cultural note:** Designed by Hiroshi Hara (1993). The basement was
              designed as a recreated Taisho-era (1912-1926) market
              street and is surprisingly convincing — the juxtaposition
              of a 1920s streetscape directly beneath a futurist tower
              is very Osaka. Entry ~1,500 yen.
        - Dinner in Fukushima neighbourhood:
            time: 7pm
            tags: [food, local, nightlife]
            note: |
              Fukushima (15 min walk from Umeda or one stop by subway)
              is where Osaka residents go for a proper evening out —
              dense with izakayas and small restaurants, without
              tourist pricing.

    - day:
        title: Southern Osaka — Shitennoji, Sumiyoshi Taisha, Hozenji at night
        time: 2026-05-16
        note: |
          A day in the historically deepest parts of Osaka — two of
          Japan's oldest religious sites, both south of central Namba.
          The Hankai tram (Japan's oldest surviving tram line) connects
          Tennoji to Sumiyoshi. Allow a full day.
        items:
        - Shitennoji Temple:
            time: 9am
            priority: must
            duration: 1h
            tags: [temple, history, cultural]
            location:
              name: Shitennoji Temple
              lat: 34.6548
              lng: 135.5165
            note: |
              Founded 593 AD by Prince Shotoku — Japan's oldest
              officially administered Buddhist temple. The five-story
              pagoda and main golden hall stand in a straight line,
              a layout copied from Korean and Chinese temples. Entry
              to the inner precinct is 300 yen.

              **Cultural note:** Prince Shotoku (574-622 AD) built Shitennoji after
              praying to the Four Heavenly Kings for victory in a
              civil war that would determine whether Buddhism became
              Japan's state religion. It did. The temple's straight
              south-north axis layout became the template for Buddhist
              architecture across Japan.
        - Hankai tram to Sumiyoshi Taisha:
            time: 10:30am
            tags: [transport, experience]
            note: |
              Board the Hankai tram (Japan's oldest surviving
              streetcar, running since 1911) from Tennoji-Ekimae
              toward Sumiyoshi-Torii-mae — 20 minutes through quiet
              residential Osaka.

              **Cultural note:** The Hankai tram runs on 90-year-old infrastructure
              through neighbourhoods where nothing is built for
              tourists. Residents use it for daily shopping and
              commuting. The tram itself is a living document of
              what Japanese cities looked like before the postwar
              rebuilding.
        - Sumiyoshi Taisha:
            priority: must
            duration: 1h
            tags: [shrine, history, architecture]
            location:
              name: Sumiyoshi Taisha
              lat: 34.6134
              lng: 135.4930
            note: |
              One of Japan's oldest and most important Shinto shrines,
              founded in the 3rd century AD — the Sumiyoshi-zukuri
              architectural style predates Chinese Buddhist influence
              and is uniquely Japanese.

              **Cultural note:** The curved drum bridge (Sorihashi) at the entrance is
              so steep that negotiating it was historically considered
              a physical act of purification. The shrine enshrines
              Shinto deities of the sea and safe passage, visited
              by sailors before voyages for centuries. The four main
              halls are arranged in a way found nowhere else in Japan.
        - Return to Namba for lunch:
            time: midday
            note: Return by tram to Tennoji, then subway to Namba. Try a gyudon (beef rice bowl) or a bowl of ramen for 
              a simple affordable lunch.

        - Hozenji Yokocho at night:
            time: 7pm
            priority: must
            duration: 1h30m
            tags: [atmosphere, cultural, food]
            location:
              name: Hozenji Yokocho
              lat: 34.6688
              lng: 135.5037
            note: |
              A narrow stone-paved alley tucked directly behind
              Dotonbori, lined with small traditional restaurants
              and bars on both sides, with a moss-covered stone Fudo
              Myo-o statue that visitors splash with water for good
              fortune.

              **Cultural note:** The Fudo Myo-o statue has been splashed with ladles
              of water for so many centuries that thick green moss
              now encases it entirely — a beautiful accretion of
              collective ritual. While Dotonbori has been thoroughly
              commercialised, Hozenji Yokocho has remained genuinely
              old Osaka — the same small kappo (counter-style)
              restaurants that have been here for decades.
    - day:
        title: Kobe day trip
        time: 2026-05-17
        note: |
          30 minutes from Osaka — JR Tokaido-Sanyo Line from Osaka
          to Kobe Sannomiya (~410 yen). Kobe is a port city with
          a genuinely cosmopolitan character unlike any other Japanese
          city, and has excellent beef and chicken options.
        items:
        - Kitano Ijinkan district:
            time: 10am
            duration: 1h30m
            tags: [history, architecture, walk]
            location:
              name: Kitano Ijinkan, Kobe
              lat: 34.6963
              lng: 135.1853
            note: |
              A hillside neighbourhood of Western-style residences
              built by foreign merchants and diplomats during Meiji-
              era Kobe's years as Japan's primary international
              trading port — over 30 restored mansions from France,
              Germany, England, the Netherlands, and the United States.

              **Cultural note:** Kobe's port was one of the first opened to foreign
              trade after 1854. The foreign residents built houses
              in their home architectural styles — the result is a
              neighbourhood that looks, from a certain angle, like
              a small European hillside village dropped into Japan.
              The juxtaposition of colonial-era mansions with Buddhist
              temples immediately below them is a precise physical
              record of Japan's cultural negotiation with the West.
        - Nada sake district:
            time: midday
            duration: 2h
            tags: [food, cultural, museum]
            location:
              name: Nada Sake District
              lat: 34.7096
              lng: 135.2552
            note: |
              Kobe's eastern waterfront of historic sake breweries —
              five major kura operate here, producing roughly 30%
              of Japan's sake output. Free entry and tastings at
              Hakutsuru and Kikumasamune brewery museums.

              **Cultural note:** Nada sake is considered Japan's finest — the Miyamizu
              water from the Rokko mountains has a specific mineral
              composition (high potassium, low iron) that produces
              a clear, dry, complex sake. Have lunch here — the
              restaurant adjacent to Kikumasamune is well-regarded.
        - Kobe beef teppanyaki dinner:
            time: 7pm
            priority: must
            tags: [food, experience]
            note: |
              Kobe beef (Wagyu cattle raised to strict standards in
              Hyogo Prefecture) served teppanyaki-style — grilled
              on a flat iron plate at the table.

              **Cultural note:** Kobe beef's marbling (sashi) results from genetics,
              feed, and the Hyogo mountain environment. The fat
              melts at body temperature — below 37C — which is why
              it has a different mouthfeel from any other beef.
              Expensive (8,000-15,000 yen per person) but genuinely
              different from anything you will eat elsewhere. Book
              in advance — Mouriya Ginza, Ishida, or Misono are
              well-regarded options near Sannomiya.
    - day:
        title: Checkout, then to Hiroshima
        time: 2026-05-18
        items:
        - Checkout and travel:
            time: 9am
            note: Nozomi Shinkansen from Shin-Osaka to Hiroshima (~1h15m). Book via Smart EX.

- train:
    from: Osaka (Shin-Osaka)
    to: Hiroshima
    note: Nozomi Shinkansen. ~1h15m. Book via Smart EX.

  # ──────────────────────────────────────────
  # HIROSHIMA (2 nights)
  # ──────────────────────────────────────────

- Hiroshima:
    arrives: 2026-05-18
    departs: 2026-05-20
    duration: 2 nights
    location: Hiroshima, Japan
    tags: [history, peace, culture, UNESCO]
    stay:
    - Smile Hotel Hiroshima:
        arrives: 2026-05-18T15:00
        departs: 2026-05-20T11:00
        location:
          address: Naka-ku Nagarekawa-cho 7-10, Hiroshima 730-0028, Japan
          lat: 34.3953
          lng: 132.4600
        info:
        - confirmation: "9190961846079502936"
        - pin: "129134"
        - check-in-number: "627693527"
        - recommended-code: 8RA7WULP
        - phone: +81 82-240-4000
        - platform: Booking.com
        - room: Double Room
        - price: 73.48 EUR — already paid
        note: Present check-in number 627693527 with photo ID.
    activities:

    - day:
        title: The Peace Memorial — the heart of Hiroshima
        time: 2026-05-18
        note: Allow a full afternoon here without rushing. This is not a day for fitting in many sights.
        items:
        - Hiroshima Peace Memorial Museum:
            time: 11am
            priority: must
            duration: 2h30m
            tags: [museum, history, UNESCO]
            location:
              name: Hiroshima Peace Memorial Museum
              lat: 34.3954
              lng: 132.4531
            note: |
              One of the world's most important museums — documenting
              the atomic bombing of August 6, 1945 through personal
              belongings, photographs, survivors' testimonies, medical
              data, and physical evidence.

              **Cultural note:** The museum's argument is not vengeful — it makes no
              case about who was right or wrong in the war. It argues
              simply that what happened here should never happen again,
              to anyone, anywhere. The most affecting objects are the
              smallest: a shadow burned into granite steps by a person
              who was sitting there at 8:15am. A child's bento box
              with charred rice. A bicycle wheel melted into the shape
              of the blast's outward force. A watch stopped at 8:15.
              Allow the full 2.5 hours.
        - Peace Memorial Park:
            time: 1:30pm
            priority: must
            duration: 1h
            tags: [history, UNESCO, walk]
            location:
              name: Hiroshima Peace Memorial Park
              lat: 34.3943
              lng: 132.4526
            note: |
              A 12-hectare park on the island at the epicentre of
              the bomb, containing the Cenotaph, the Children's Peace
              Monument, the Peace Flame, and direct sightlines to
              the A-Bomb Dome.

              **Cultural note:** Designed by Kenzo Tange (1954) with the Cenotaph
              precisely aligned so that through its arch you see
              the Peace Flame and, beyond it, the Dome — a deliberate
              visual axis connecting commemoration to evidence.
              The Peace Flame has burned continuously since 1964
              — it will be extinguished only when all nuclear weapons
              in the world are eliminated.
        - A-Bomb Dome (Genbaku Dome):
            priority: must
            duration: 30m
            tags: [history, UNESCO, landmark]
            location:
              name: Genbaku Dome
              lat: 34.3955
              lng: 132.4530
            note: |
              The steel-and-brick skeleton of the Hiroshima Prefectural
              Industrial Promotion Hall — preserved exactly as the
              atomic blast left it, 580 metres from the hypocentre.

              **Cultural note:** The building survived because the blast came from almost
              directly above, compressing the dome downward rather
              than sideways. It is the only structure near the
              hypocentre not demolished in the aftermath. Listed as
              a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1996 despite objections
              from the US and China. It remains the most physically
              direct encounter with nuclear warfare that exists anywhere
              on earth.
        - Hiroshima okonomiyaki dinner:
            time: 7pm
            priority: must
            tags: [food, local specialty]
            note: |
              Okonomi-mura ("okonomiyaki village") has multiple stalls
              on different floors of one building — sit at the counter
              and watch it made in front of you. Order with pork (buta)
              without seafood toppings.

              Hiroshima-style okonomiyaki is layered — batter, cabbage,
              bean sprouts, noodles, pork, and egg cooked in distinct
              strata rather than mixed. A different dish from Osaka's
              version.

    - day:
        title: Miyajima Island — the floating torii
        time: 2026-05-19
        note: |
          Depart early. JR Sanyo Line from Hiroshima to Miyajimaguchi
          (~25 min), then JR Ferry (10 min) to Miyajima. Check tide
          times at jma.go.jp before going — high tide means the torii
          floats; low tide means you can walk to it. Both are beautiful.
        items:
        - Itsukushima Shrine and the floating torii:
            time: 9am
            priority: must
            duration: 1h
            tags: [shrine, UNESCO, landmark, photography]
            location:
              name: Itsukushima Shrine
              lat: 34.2960
              lng: 132.3197
            note: |
              A Shinto shrine built on pilings over the water —
              at high tide the entire vermilion complex appears to
              float, with the great torii gate rising from the sea
              200 metres offshore.

              **Cultural note:** Originally built 593 AD; rebuilt in its current form
              1168 by the warlord Taira no Kiyomori. The island
              itself is sacred — historically death and birth were
              forbidden here. The torii gate's current structure
              dates to 1875; it is the 8th iteration since the 6th
              century. Entry 300 yen.
        - Senjokaku Hall:
            duration: 30m
            tags: [temple, history]
            note: |
              An immense unfinished wooden hall on the hillside above
              Itsukushima — Toyotomi Hideyoshi began it in 1587 and
              it was never completed after his death.

              **Cultural note:** Hideyoshi planned to recite sutras for the war dead
              here. When he died in 1598, the hall stood open to
              the sky, its interior hung with harvest goods, fans,
              and wooden plaques by those who came after. It has
              remained this way for 400 years — the largest
              unfinished wooden building in Japan.
        - Mount Misen:
            priority: must
            duration: 3h
            tags: [hiking, nature, spiritual]
            location:
              name: Mount Misen
              lat: 34.2862
              lng: 132.3234
            note: |
              Miyajima's sacred mountain (530m) — the main trail
              through old-growth forest takes 1.5 hours up, passing
              wild deer and sometimes macaques before emerging at
              the summit with 360° views of the Seto Inland Sea.

              **Cultural note:** Kobo Daishi (Kukai, 774-835 AD), founder of Shingon
              Buddhism in Japan, established a temple here in 806 AD
              and lit a flame that has never been extinguished in
              1,200 years. The same flame was used in 1964 to light
              the Peace Flame in Hiroshima's Peace Memorial Park
              — connecting Japan's most sacred fire to its most painful
              modern history. Take the ropeway up (1,800 yen return)
              and hike down through Momijidani forest, or reverse.
        - Lunch and momiji manju:
            time: midday
            note: |
              Momiji manju (maple-leaf cakes with sweet red bean
              filling) are Miyajima's signature confection. For a
              proper meal, the restaurants near the ferry terminal
              serve tofu and vegetable set lunches.

        - Return and evening in Nagarekawa:
            time: 4pm
            note: |
              Back in Hiroshima by late afternoon. The Nagarekawa-cho
              bar district (close to the hotel) is Hiroshima's liveliest
              evening neighbourhood. Try local Saijo sake.

    - day:
        title: Checkout, then to Kyoto
        time: 2026-05-20
        items:
        - Checkout and travel:
            time: 10am
            note: Nozomi Shinkansen from Hiroshima to Kyoto (~55 min). Book via Smart EX.

- train:
    from: Hiroshima
    to: Kyoto
    note: Nozomi Shinkansen. ~55 min. Book via Smart EX.

  # ──────────────────────────────────────────
  # KYOTO (17 nights)
  # ──────────────────────────────────────────

- Kyoto:
    arrives: 2026-05-20
    departs: 2026-06-06
    duration: 17 nights
    location: Kyoto, Japan
    tags: [temples, culture, history, shrines, food, geisha, zen, gardens]
    note: |
      Kyoto is Japan's soul — over 2,000 temples and shrines, 17 UNESCO
      World Heritage sites, preserved geisha districts, and some of
      the country's finest cuisine. With 17 nights you have the rare
      gift of time. Go slowly. Return to places that moved you.

      A key advantage of staying 17 nights: you can visit popular places
      at dawn (before crowds) and return in the evening (when they're
      lit differently). Fushimi Inari is a genuinely different place
      at 6am versus 10am.

      Late May and early June: wisteria, iris, and early hydrangea
      season. Temperatures 20-27C, occasional rain. Rainy season
      typically begins in Kyoto around June 5-10. Rainy Kyoto temples
      — especially moss gardens and stone paths after rain — are among
      the most beautiful things Japan offers.
    stay:
    - RIHGA Place Kyoto Shijo Karasuma:
        arrives: 2026-05-20T15:00
        departs: 2026-05-22T11:00
        location:
          address: Shomogyo-Ku Sannocho 551, Kyoto
          lat: 35.0028
          lng: 135.7585
        info:
        - confirmation: "5151688310"
        - pin: "2031"
        - platform: Booking.com
        - room: King Room
        - cancellation: free until May 17, 2026 at 11:59 PM JST
        - price: 132.10 EUR — pay at property

    - INA HOUSE GION:
        arrives: 2026-05-22T15:00
        departs: 2026-06-06T05:00
        location:
          address: Kyoto 44-24, Japan
          lat: 35.0035
          lng: 135.7753
        info:
        - confirmation: "5266033075"
        - pin: "1290"
        - phone: 819071700039
        - platform: Booking.com
        - room: Double Room with Private Bathroom
        - price: 210,953 yen — already paid (non-refundable)
        note: |
          Non-refundable. No date changes possible. Apartment with
          kitchen in the Gion district — you can walk from the front
          door directly into one of the most beautiful neighbourhoods
          in Japan.

    activities:

    - day:
        title: Arrival, Nishiki Market, Gion at dusk
        time: 2026-05-20
        items:
        - Arrive from Hiroshima:
            time: midday
            note: Hotel check-in from 3pm. Store bags and go directly to Nishiki Market — it closes in the early 
              evening.

        - Nishiki Market:
            time: 2pm
            priority: must
            duration: 1h30m
            tags: [market, food, cultural]
            location:
              name: Nishiki Market
              lat: 35.0047
              lng: 135.7659
            note: |
              A 400m covered shopping street of 130 specialist vendors
              selling pickled vegetables, fresh tofu, roasted skewers,
              sesame tofu, matcha sweets, and Kyoto's signature
              prepared foods in a centuries-old arcade.

              **Cultural note:** Known as Kyoto's Kitchen since the Edo period — the
              market has supplied Kyoto's restaurants, temples, and
              households with specialist ingredients since the 10th
              century. Try warabi mochi (bracken-starch jelly sweets),
              pickled cucumber on a stick, and freshly made sesame
              tofu. The preservation of this street-level artisan food
              culture in a modern city is not accidental.
        - Gion evening walk:
            time: 5pm
            priority: must
            duration: 2h
            tags: [geisha, historical, cultural, neighbourhood]
            location:
              name: Gion, Kyoto
              lat: 35.0036
              lng: 135.7752
            note: |
              The window between 5:30 and 7pm is the best for spotting
              maiko walking between appointments. Gion Shirakawa canal
              and the lantern-lit approach to Yasaka Shrine are
              beautiful at this hour.

              Kyoto's historic geisha district — Hanamikoji Street's
              ochaya (tea houses), Shirakawa canal's willow trees,
              and the small lanes of Gion Shinbashi largely unchanged
              since the 18th century.

              **Cultural note:** Gion's geisha culture (geiko and their apprentice maiko)
              dates to the 7th century. The ochaya system — private
              teahouses accessible only by introduction — has persisted
              for 300 years. Maiko (aged 15-20) undergo 5 years of
              training. Walk quietly; do not block their path or use
              flash photography. Miyagawa-cho (the parallel geisha
              district, south of Gion) is quieter and more authentic.

        - Obanzai dinner:
            time: 8pm
            tags: [food, Kyoto cuisine]
            note: |
              Kyoto-style home cooking — small seasonal dishes of
              simmered vegetables, tofu, pickles, and egg dishes
              served in small portions over rice.

              **Cultural note:** Obanzai developed from the Buddhist temple food tradition
              and the practice of using every part of an ingredient
              without waste — a reflection of Kyoto's landlocked
              geography requiring a cuisine of refinement without
              relying on fresh seafood. Many dishes are intensely
              vegetable-forward and exactly suited to your preferences.
    - day:
        title: Fushimi Inari at dawn, then Uji
        time: 2026-05-21
        note: Set an alarm. The dawn visit to Fushimi Inari is the most important timing call of the entire trip.
        items:
        - Fushimi Inari Taisha at dawn:
            time: 6am
            priority: must
            duration: 2h
            tags: [shrine, UNESCO, nature, hiking, dawn]
            location:
              name: Fushimi Inari Taisha
              lat: 34.9671
              lng: 135.7727
            note: |
              The Yotsutsuji intersection (40 min up) has a city view
              and is where most visitors turn back. Continue another
              20 minutes to the summit — the upper mountain has small
              atmospheric sub-shrines almost never visited.

              A Shinto shrine complex on Mount Inari where 10,000+
              vermilion torii gates form tunnels climbing 4km up the
              mountain through forested hillsides — the most iconic
              image of Kyoto, and one of the most photographed places
              in Japan.

              **Cultural note:** The torii gates are donated by businesses — the donor's
              name and date of donation are carved on the back of
              each. Gates donated in the 18th century stand beside
              ones donated last year. Inari is the Shinto deity of
              rice, agriculture, business, and foxes — the fox
              (kitsune) is the divine messenger. At 6am you have
              this to yourself. By 9am tour buses arrive. By 10am
              it is one of the most crowded places in Japan.

        - Uji:
            time: 10am
            priority: must
            duration: 4h
            tags: [UNESCO, temple, food, tea, nature]
            location:
              name: Uji City, Kyoto Prefecture
              lat: 34.8841
              lng: 135.7981
            note: |
              Byodo-in (600 yen) — book timed entry in advance.
              Ujikami Shrine (Japan's oldest surviving Shinto shrine
              structure, 1060 AD) is 5 minutes across the river.
              Nakamura Tokichi tea house (Meiji-era) for a proper
              matcha with wagashi sweets. Matcha soft-serve from
              any of the stalls.

              A small city 30 minutes south of Kyoto — home to
              Byodo-in (UNESCO, the Phoenix Hall depicted on the
              10-yen coin), the Uji River walk, Japan's oldest
              shrine, and the country's finest matcha production.

              **Cultural note:** Uji is where The Tale of Genji — written by Murasaki
              Shikibu around 1010 AD, considered the world's first
              novel — concludes. The city has produced matcha since
              the 13th century when a Buddhist monk brought tea seeds
              from China. Tea plants are covered with straw before
              harvest to concentrate chlorophyll, producing the bright
              green colour and umami depth of high-grade matcha.

    - day:
        title: Arashiyama at dawn, then move to INA HOUSE GION
        time: 2026-05-22
        note: Another early alarm. Arashiyama's bamboo grove is transformed at 7am.
        items:
        - Arashiyama Bamboo Grove and Tenryu-ji:
            time: 7am
            priority: must
            duration: 3h
            tags: [nature, UNESCO, temple, dawn]
            location:
              name: Arashiyama Bamboo Grove
              lat: 35.0170
              lng: 135.6720
            note: |
              After the bamboo, enter Tenryu-ji garden (500 yen garden,
              800 yen with interior — the interior is worth it).
              Then cross Togetsukyo Bridge and walk 10 minutes uphill
              to Jojakko-ji.

              A dense grove of giant bamboo in Tenryu-ji's grounds
              — the stalks rise 20+ metres, creating filtered light
              and a resonant creaking sound in the wind that UNESCO
              has listed among Japan's 100 Soundscapes.

              **Cultural note:** The bamboo grove is technically part of Tenryu-ji's
              garden, founded 1339 by shogun Ashikaga Takauji.
              Tenryu-ji pioneered the "borrowed scenery" (shakkei)
              technique — the mountains behind are incorporated
              into the garden's composition as if they belong to it.
              At 7am you may have the bamboo path entirely to
              yourself. By 8:30am it is full.

        - Jojakko-ji Temple:
            priority: must
            duration: 45m
            tags: [temple, moss garden, atmosphere]
            location:
              name: Jojakko-ji Temple
              lat: 35.0269
              lng: 135.6699
            note: |
              A small Nichiren temple reached via a stone stairway
              through ancient cedar trees, with a moss garden, a
              weathered pagoda half-hidden by maple branches, and
              almost no visitors. Entry 500 yen.

              **Cultural note:** Founded 1596 as a hermitage for the priest Nikkei.
              Famous in autumn for maple foliage, but in May the
              moss is extraordinary — a deep, luminous green covering
              every stone and root. One of those places that feels
              like a genuine discovery even though it is not hidden.
        - Checkout RIHGA, check into INA HOUSE GION:
            time: midday
            note: |
              RIHGA checkout at 11am. INA HOUSE check-in from 3pm.
              The two are about 20 minutes' walk apart in central
              Kyoto. Your Gion home for 15 nights.

        # ─────────────────────────────────────────
        # KYOTO LONG STAY — circuits and plans
        # Arrange these across the 14 remaining
        # nights to suit weather and energy.
        # ─────────────────────────────────────────

    - plan:
        title: "Circuit A — Eastern Higashiyama Walk"
        note: |
          A natural walking route east from the Gion apartment,
          climbing gently into the hills. Best on a weekday morning,
          starting by 8am. The full circuit takes 3-4 hours at a
          comfortable pace. Return at dusk for Kiyomizudera's evening
          light.
        items:
        - Yasaka Shrine:
            tags: [shrine, cultural, neighbourhood]
            location:
              name: Yasaka Shrine
              lat: 35.0037
              lng: 135.7784
            note: |
              The shrine at the east end of Shijo-dori — free to
              enter at any hour, lantern-lit at night, the main hall
              reflected in stone lanterns.

              **Cultural note:** Founded 656 AD. The Gion Matsuri festival held each
              July centres on this shrine — one of Japan's three
              great festivals. The shrine grounds are a genuine
              community space: locals walk dogs here in the morning,
              children play after school.
        - Maruyama Park:
            tags: [park, nature, local]
            note: |
              Kyoto's central public park adjacent to Yasaka — famous
              for its enormous weeping cherry tree, bare but
              extraordinary even in leaf in May. The small food stalls
              operating morning through evening are genuinely local.
        - Chion-in Temple:
            tags: [temple, cultural, history]
            location:
              name: Chion-in Temple
              lat: 35.0088
              lng: 135.7830
            note: |
              Headquarters of the Jodo Buddhist sect — the main gate
              (sanmon) is the largest wooden gate in Japan, and the
              main hall holds 3,000 tatami mats.

              **Cultural note:** Founded by the monk Honen (1133-1212), who taught that
              all beings — not just monks and scholars — could achieve
              salvation through sincere recitation of Amida Buddha's
              name. This revolutionary democratisation of Buddhism
              made the temple enormously popular. The bell here weighs
              70 tonnes and requires 17 monks to ring it.
        - Kodai-ji Temple:
            priority: must
            tags: [temple, zen, garden, cultural]
            location:
              name: Kodai-ji Temple
              lat: 35.0013
              lng: 135.7825
            note: |
              Founded 1606 by Nene, widow of Toyotomi Hideyoshi —
              a beautifully preserved Zen complex with teahouses, a
              bamboo grove, and a moon-viewing pavilion above a pond.

              **Cultural note:** Nene (1548-1624) outlived Hideyoshi by 26 years and
              spent them here in Buddhist retirement. She was
              Hideyoshi's closest confidante throughout his rise from
              peasant to national ruler. The temple reflects her taste:
              refined without ostentation.
        - Ninen-zaka and Sannen-zaka:
            priority: must
            tags: [historical street, Edo, cultural]
            note: |
              Two connected stone-paved lanes of Edo-period machiya
              (townhouses) — one of Japan's most intact historic
              streetscapes.

              **Cultural note:** The names mean Two-year slope and Three-year slope —
              legend says falling on either brings years of bad luck.
              The machiya architecture shows the "eel's bed" style:
              long narrow buildings (to minimise frontage tax) with
              multiple interior courtyards. Walk before 9am or
              after 5pm to avoid tour groups.
        - Kiyomizudera Temple:
            priority: must
            tags: [temple, UNESCO, viewpoint, cultural]
            location:
              name: Kiyomizudera
              lat: 34.9949
              lng: 135.7850
            note: |
              Return at dusk — the valley lit in soft orange light,
              with the pagoda silhouette against the sky, is one
              of Kyoto's most beautiful moments.

              A great temple on a forested hillside with a wooden
              stage extending 13 metres over the valley below —
              supported by 139 pillars without a single nail.

              **Cultural note:** Founded 780 AD by the monk Enchin after a vision of
              Kannon. The phrase "jumping off the Kiyomizu stage"
              is a Japanese idiom for making a bold irreversible
              decision — so many people historically jumped as a
              test of faith that it was eventually banned. The Otowa
              waterfall below has three streams: longevity, love,
              and academic success. Entry 500 yen.

    - plan:
        title: "Circuit B — Northern Higashiyama and the Philosopher's Path"
        note: |
          A northward walk from the Gion apartment into the quieter
          temple zone along the canal. Best on a weekday, starting
          at Nanzen-ji and walking north. Allow 4-5 hours.
        items:
        - Nanzen-ji Temple:
            priority: must
            tags: [temple, zen, UNESCO, architecture]
            location:
              name: Nanzen-ji Temple
              lat: 35.0115
              lng: 135.7923
            note: |
              One of Japan's most important Zen complexes — the great
              Sanmon gate, the Hojo's famous rock garden, and a Roman
              brick aqueduct from 1890 running directly through the
              temple grounds.

              **Cultural note:** Established 1291. The aqueduct (Suirokaku) was built
              to carry Lake Biwa water to Kyoto during Meiji-era
              modernisation. The decision to route it through one
              of Japan's most sacred Buddhist complexes was
              extraordinary and is now considered a masterpiece of
              cultural integration. The Hojo's Leaping Tiger garden
              costs 500 yen.
        - Philosopher's Path (Tetsugaku-no-Michi):
            priority: must
            tags: [walk, canal, nature, literary]
            location:
              name: Philosopher's Path, Kyoto
              lat: 35.0208
              lng: 135.7955
            note: |
              A 2km canal-side path lined with cherry trees (lush
              green in late May) between Nanzen-ji and Ginkaku-ji
              — named after philosopher Nishida Kitaro who walked
              it daily while teaching at Kyoto University.

              **Cultural note:** Nishida Kitaro (1870-1945) developed his philosophy
              of "pure experience" — an attempt to reconcile Zen
              Buddhist thought with Western phenomenology. He walked
              this path every morning. Hundreds of Kyoto school
              philosophers have used it since, making it a public
              space with genuine intellectual lineage. Walk slowly.
        - Honen-in:
            priority: must
            tags: [temple, hidden gem, garden]
            location:
              name: Honen-in
              lat: 35.0237
              lng: 135.7966
            note: |
              A small thatched-gate temple at the end of a narrow
              forest path off the Philosopher's Path — two raked
              sand mounds frame the approach, their patterns changed
              seasonally. Free entry.

              **Cultural note:** Founded 1680 by disciples of the monk Honen. The sand
              mounds (shiradama-suna) are raked differently for each
              season — they represent the pure water that purifies
              those who pass between them. One of Kyoto's most
              quietly beautiful places. Check opening hours in advance.
        - Ginkaku-ji (Silver Pavilion):
            tags: [temple, garden, UNESCO, cultural]
            location:
              name: Ginkaku-ji
              lat: 35.0270
              lng: 135.7985
            note: |
              The Silver Pavilion — which is neither silver nor a
              conventional pavilion, but a masterpiece of Higashiyama
              culture, with a dry sand garden featuring the famous
              conical Kogetsudai (Moon-Viewing Platform).

              **Cultural note:** Built 1490 by shogun Ashikaga Yoshimasa as a retirement
              villa. Silver leaf was planned but never applied —
              Yoshimasa died during construction. The Kogetsudai sand
              cone (1.8m high) was designed to reflect moonlight into
              the garden at night, creating an artificial moon on the
              ground — a refinement of aesthetic contemplation that
              required extraordinary confidence in subtle beauty.
              Entry 500 yen.
    - plan:
        title: "Circuit C — Northwest Kyoto (Golden Temple circuit)"
        note: |
          Kinkaku-ji, Ryoan-ji, and Ninna-ji are within comfortable
          walking distance. Start at Kinkaku-ji at exactly 9am before
          tour groups descend.
        items:
        - Kinkaku-ji (Golden Pavilion):
            priority: must
            tags: [temple, UNESCO, landmark, cultural]
            location:
              name: Kinkaku-ji
              lat: 35.0394
              lng: 135.7292
            note: |
              A three-storey pavilion covered in real gold leaf,
              reflected in the mirror surface of Kyoko-chi Pond —
              genuinely one of the most beautiful structures built
              by human hands. Entry 400 yen.

              **Cultural note:** Built 1397 by shogun Ashikaga Yoshimitsu. The current
              pavilion is a 1955 reconstruction — the original was
              burned in 1950 by a young Buddhist novice monk who,
              by his own account, was overwhelmed by its beauty and
              could not bear that it would outlast him. Mishima Yukio's
              novel The Temple of the Golden Pavilion (1956) tells
              the arsonist's psychology. Go at 9am.
        - Ryoan-ji:
            priority: must
            tags: [temple, zen, garden, UNESCO]
            location:
              name: Ryoan-ji
              lat: 35.0345
              lng: 135.7182
            note: |
              Japan's most famous Zen rock garden — fifteen stones
              arranged in raked white gravel within a walled enclosure.
              From any seated position, only fourteen stones are
              visible. Entry 600 yen.

              **Cultural note:** Created around 1500 by an unknown designer. No single
              interpretation has ever been accepted — the garden has
              been read as islands in a sea, tigers crossing a river,
              and as a representation of nothingness itself. The
              author's anonymity is almost certainly deliberate.
              The one hidden stone — whichever angle you approach
              from, one is always behind another — may be the garden's
              most precise statement. Sit on the veranda in silence.
        - Ninna-ji Temple:
            tags: [temple, UNESCO, imperial, cultural]
            location:
              name: Ninna-ji
              lat: 35.0313
              lng: 135.7156
            note: |
              A vast imperial temple with a five-story pagoda and
              a beautifully preserved Shinden (ceremonial hall).

              **Cultural note:** Founded 888 AD by Emperor Uda, who retired here as
              a monk — establishing the tradition of monk-emperors
              at Ninna-ji that continued for 1,000 years. The abbots
              were always imperial princes, making it the most
              aristocratic temple in Japan. Free outer precinct;
              500 yen for the Shinden garden.
        - Koryu-ji Temple:
            priority: maybe
            tags: [temple, sculpture, history, hidden gem]
            location:
              name: Koryu-ji Temple
              lat: 35.0111
              lng: 135.6973
            note: |
              30 min by bus from Ninna-ji (bus 61 or 62 toward Uzumasa).

              Kyoto's oldest temple, housing the Miroku Bosatsu —
              a carved cypress wood bodhisattva in a half-lotus pose,
              considered one of the most beautiful sculptures in the
              world. Entry 800 yen.

              **Cultural note:** Founded 622 AD, predating Kyoto as Japan's capital.
              The Miroku Bosatsu (Contemplative Bodhisattva) is 87cm
              tall, carved from a single piece of Japanese red pine
              in the late 6th century. Its expression — a slight
              smile, one hand raised to the face in thought — has
              moved visitors to silence for 1,400 years. In 1960,
              a university student was so overcome while looking at
              it that he touched the statue's hand; the finger broke.
              He was convicted of cultural property destruction.


    - plan:
        title: "Circuit D — Central Kyoto"
        note: |
          A slower, more urban Kyoto day — the castle, the market,
          and the evening canal. All within comfortable walking distance
          of each other and the Gion apartment.
        items:
        - Nijo Castle:
            priority: must
            tags: [castle, history, UNESCO, cultural]
            location:
              name: Nijo Castle
              lat: 35.0142
              lng: 135.7481
            note: |
              The Tokugawa shogunate's Kyoto palace — the Ninomaru
              Palace interior features extraordinary painted screens
              by Kano school masters and the famous nightingale floors
              that squeak as you walk, designed to alert guards of
              any approach. Entry 1,300 yen.

              **Cultural note:** Built 1626 for the third Tokugawa shogun Iemitsu. The
              nightingale floors (uguisubari) were engineered by
              placing small metal clamps between floorboards — the
              weight of a foot compresses the clamps, which squeak.
              Silent infiltration is impossible. In 1868 in this
              building, the last Tokugawa shogun announced the
              restoration of imperial rule — ending 265 years of
              shogunate government. The room where he made this
              declaration is marked.
        - Nishiki Market (return):
            tags: [food, market]
            note: Return to graze slowly — now that you know what you liked on the first visit.

        - Pontocho lane at dusk:
            tags: [neighbourhood, restaurant, cultural, atmospheric]
            location:
              name: Pontocho, Kyoto
              lat: 35.0054
              lng: 135.7702
            note: |
              A narrow lantern-lit alley of restaurants and bars
              running parallel to the Kamo River — Kyoto's most
              atmospheric dining lane, with wooden machiya facades
              hiding kaiseki restaurants, tofu specialists, and
              sake bars.

              **Cultural note:** One of Kyoto's five geisha districts. In summer
              (June-September), restaurants build yuka platforms over
              the Kamo River for outdoor dining — one of Kyoto's
              defining summer pleasures. The season starts in June,
              which means you may catch the early yuka if the weather
              cooperates.
    - plan:
        title: "Tea ceremony"
        note: |
          Book a session near the Gion apartment. Urasenke (the main
          school of tea ceremony) has its headquarters in Kyoto and
          offers visitor sessions. En tea ceremony (Gion area) and
          Camellia Tea Experience (Gion area) also offer small-group
          or private sessions. Book in advance. Cost: 2,000-5,000 yen.
        items:
        - Formal tea ceremony session:
            priority: must
            tags: [cultural, experience, Zen]
            note: |
              A guided session of chado (the way of tea) — preparation
              of powdered matcha in a tatami room following the gestures
              and protocol developed over 500 years.

              **Cultural note:** Sen no Rikyu (1522-1591) codified the tea ceremony as
              a practice of spiritual concentration — every gesture
              (the way the cloth is folded, the direction of rotation
              of the bowl, the angle of the ladle) is prescribed and
              meaningful. The ceremony is also a study in impermanence
              (wabi-sabi) — the most prized tea bowls are irregular,
              cracked, repaired with gold lacquer (kintsugi). Each
              scar becomes part of the object's beauty.
    - plan:
        title: "Day trip — Nara"
        note: |
          45 min from Kyoto by Kintetsu Kyoto Line to Kintetsu-Nara
          (760 yen each — faster than JR, recommended). Full day.
          Nara is the right size for a long slow day.
        items:
        - Todai-ji Temple and the Great Buddha:
            priority: must
            tags: [temple, history, UNESCO, landmark]
            location:
              name: Todai-ji Temple
              lat: 34.6888
              lng: 135.8398
            note: |
              The world's largest wooden building housing a 15-metre
              bronze Buddha — the scale is overwhelming on arrival,
              the interior smell of incense and old timber exactly
              what you expect and also nothing like you imagine.
              Entry 600 yen.

              **Cultural note:** Built 745 AD by Emperor Shomu to consolidate imperial
              power and unify Japan under Buddhism. The bronze
              Daibutsu took 3 years to cast, using all of Japan's
              known bronze reserves and ruining the national economy.
              The pillar inside with the hole (the same size as the
              Buddha's nostril) was installed for visitors to squeeze
              through — those who fit are promised enlightenment.
        - Nara Deer Park:
            priority: must
            tags: [nature, cultural, experience]
            location:
              name: Nara Deer Park
              lat: 34.6841
              lng: 135.8440
            note: |
              Over 1,200 wild sika deer roam freely through Nara
              Park and the surrounding streets, considered sacred
              messengers of the Shinto gods.

              **Cultural note:** The deer have been considered sacred since 768 AD,
              when the god Takemikazuchi-no-Mikoto was said to
              arrive riding a white deer. Killing a Nara deer was
              a capital offence until 1637. They are officially
              designated National Treasure animals. They have learned
              to bow when they see shika senbei crackers (200 yen)
              — a conditioned behaviour producing an experience of
              apparent courtesy. Guard your bags.
        - Kasuga Taisha Shrine:
            priority: must
            tags: [shrine, UNESCO, historical]
            location:
              name: Kasuga Taisha
              lat: 34.6813
              lng: 135.8480
            note: |
              A UNESCO shrine at the end of a forest path lined with
              3,000 stone and bronze lanterns, the inner sanctuary
              glowing with hanging lanterns lit twice yearly.

              **Cultural note:** Founded 768 AD by the Fujiwara clan — Japan's most
              powerful aristocratic family for 400 years. The shrine
              enshrines four deities including Amenokoyane-no-Mikoto,
              patron of scholarship, to whom Japanese students still
              pray before examinations.
        - Naramachi:
            tags: [neighbourhood, historical, walk, lunch]
            note: |
              Have lunch here. Look for kama-meshi (clay pot rice). Walk back through the deer park to the station.

              The preserved old merchant quarter south of Todai-ji
              — narrow lanes of traditional machiya, small shops,
              and local restaurants.


    - plan:
        title: "Overnight trip — Koyasan"
        note: |
          Two days, one night. The most important overnight trip
          of the Kyoto long stay and should not be skipped.

          Route from Kyoto: Kyoto > Osaka (Namba) by JR or Kintetsu,
          then Nankai Koya Line to Gokurakubashi, then 5-minute
          cable car up the mountain. Total: ~2.5 hours.

          Book shukubo (temple lodging) well in advance — Eko-in
          or Rengejoin are recommended.
        items:
        - Okunoin Cemetery:
            priority: must
            tags: [cemetery, spiritual, UNESCO, atmosphere]
            location:
              name: Okunoin, Koyasan
              lat: 34.2171
              lng: 135.5944
            note: |
              The inner sanctuary (Toro-do, hall of 10,000 lanterns) is open 24 hours. No photography in the inner hall.

              A 2km forest path through 200,000 grave markers
              to the inner sanctuary of Kobo Daishi — Japan's most
              sacred Buddhist site, where the saint is believed to
              be in eternal meditation.

              **Cultural note:** Kobo Daishi (Kukai, 774-835 AD) founded Koyasan as
              a centre for Shingon Buddhism. He is not believed to
              have died — according to Shingon teaching, he entered
              nyujo (deep meditation) in 835 and remains in this
              state awaiting Maitreya (the next Buddha). Food is
              still brought to him twice daily in the inner sanctuary.
              The path passes under 1,000-year-old cedar trees,
              past markers for samurai, emperors, and feudal lords,
              alongside corporate monuments from Nissin Cup Noodle
              and Panasonic. Visit at dusk; return at dawn.


        - Kongobu-ji Temple:
            priority: must
            tags: [temple, cultural, UNESCO, garden]
            note: |
              The head temple of Shingon Buddhism, housing the
              largest rock garden in Japan (Banryutei — two dragons
              emerging from a sea of clouds rendered in granite).
              Entry 1,000 yen.

              **Cultural note:** Founded by Kobo Daishi in 819 AD. The main hall's
              sliding screen paintings (fusuma-e) by the Kano school
              are extraordinary.
        - Shukubo (temple lodging):
            note: |
              Stay overnight in a monastery guesthouse — tatami
              rooms, communal baths fed by natural springs, vegetarian
              kaiseki dinner (shojin ryori), and participation in
              morning prayers at 6am.

              **Cultural note:** Shojin ryori (temple vegetarian cuisine) developed in
              Japanese Buddhist monasteries over 1,200 years — it
              relies entirely on vegetables, tofu, sesame, and kombu
              dashi. The morning goma fire ceremony involves fire,
              chanting, incense, and monks burning wooden sticks
              bearing the wishes of the living. The sound of temple
              drums at dawn in this mountain monastery is not easily
              forgotten.
        - Garan Complex (morning):
            note: |
              Koyasan's central religious campus — the Konpon Daito
              pagoda (a remarkable orange two-story pagoda housing
              five Buddha statues representing the universe), the
              Saito West Pagoda, and the Fudo-do Hall.

              **Cultural note:** The Konpon Daito was built by Kobo Daishi as a
              three-dimensional mandala. Daishi believed pilgrims
              who entered this space were literally entering the
              centre of the cosmos.
    - plan:
        title: "Day trip — Kurama and Kibune"
        note: |
          Eizan Railway from Demachiyanagi Station (northeast Kyoto)
          to Kurama, ~30 minutes. Hike over the mountain to Kibune.
          Return to Kyoto via Kibune-guchi. Full day.
        items:
        - Kurama-dera Temple:
            priority: must
            tags: [temple, hiking, spiritual, mountain]
            location:
              name: Kurama-dera
              lat: 35.1154
              lng: 135.7709
            note: |
              The funicular (200 yen) goes partway up. The full climb to the inner sanctuary takes 30-40 minutes and is worth every step.

              A mountain temple of intense spiritual atmosphere —
              the path from the gate climbs through ancient cedar
              forest to the main hall, then continues to the inner
              sanctuary at the summit.

              **Cultural note:** Kurama-yama is believed to be the dwelling of Sojobo,
              king of the tengu (mountain spirits). The 12th-century
              warrior Minamoto no Yoshitsune trained in swordsmanship
              here under the tengu's instruction, according to legend.
              In 1922, Mikao Usui experienced his spiritual awakening
              on this mountain and subsequently developed Reiki
              healing from it. The mountain carries more spiritual
              weight per square kilometre than anywhere else near Kyoto.


        - Hike Kurama to Kibune:
            priority: must
            duration: 1h
            tags: [hiking, nature, forest]
            note: |
              A 45-60 minute forest trail over the mountain ridge
              — well-marked, through old-growth cedar and cypress,
              descending into the Kibune River valley.
        - Kawadoko dining at Kibune:
            priority: must
            tags: [food, experience, seasonal]
            location:
              name: Kibune, Kyoto
              lat: 35.1162
              lng: 135.7593
            note: |
              Riverside restaurants set tables on platforms over the
              Kibune River in summer — you eat with the mountain
              stream flowing beneath your feet.

              **Cultural note:** Kawadoko (river deck) dining begins in June and runs
              through September — the cool mountain air and water
              make these the most sought-after summer lunch tables
              in the Kansai region. Call ahead about seafood-free
              options. Even without a full meal, sit at one of the
              riverside cafes and have matcha and sweets while
              listening to the river below.
    - plan:
        title: "Day trip — Himeji Castle"
        note: |
          1 hour from Kyoto by Nozomi Shinkansen to Himeji (~3,000
          yen each). Book via Smart EX. Arrive Himeji Station by 9am
          — the castle opens at 9am and tour groups arrive by 10am.
          Book entry tickets online in advance.
        items:
        - Himeji Castle:
            priority: must
            tags: [castle, UNESCO, history, architecture]
            location:
              name: Himeji Castle
              lat: 34.8394
              lng: 134.6939
            note: |
              Japan's finest surviving feudal castle — a UNESCO
              World Heritage site and National Treasure, nicknamed
              White Heron Castle for its brilliant white plaster.
              Fully intact, never bombed. Entry 1,000 yen.

              **Cultural note:** Unlike most of Japan's famous castles (Osaka, Hiroshima,
              Nagoya), Himeji was never destroyed and never
              reconstructed. The current structure dates primarily
              to 1609. The seven-story keep contains a labyrinthine
              maze of narrow corridors, hidden rooms, and passages
              designed to confuse invaders. The castle has never
              fallen. A bomb that landed in the grounds in 1945
              reportedly failed to detonate.
        - Koko-en Garden:
            duration: 45m
            tags: [garden, nature]
            note: |
              Entry 310 yen. Combined ticket with the castle available.

              A traditional garden of nine separate sub-gardens
              adjacent to the castle, recreated in 1992 on the
              original site of the feudal lord's west compound.


    - plan:
        title: "Circuit E — Arashiyama extended"
        note: A slower return to Arashiyama for the places missed on the dawn visit. Go mid-morning, not at dawn.
        items:
        - Daikaku-ji Temple:
            tags: [temple, imperial, garden]
            location:
              name: Daikaku-ji
              lat: 35.0263
              lng: 135.6640
            note: |
              An imperial villa converted to a Shingon temple, with
              Japan's oldest ornamental garden pond (Osawa Pond, 9th
              century) and an extraordinary collection of painted
              screens.

              **Cultural note:** Founded 876 AD by Emperor Saga. Osawa Pond was used
              for imperial moon-viewing parties. The Saga school of
              ikebana (flower arrangement) originated here and still
              teaches here today.
        - Adashino Nembutsu-ji Temple:
            priority: must
            tags: [temple, history, atmosphere, remote]
            location:
              name: Adashino Nembutsu-ji
              lat: 35.0330
              lng: 135.6572
            note: |
              A remote temple holding 8,000 stone Buddha figures
              gathered from the field where the bodies of the nameless
              dead were historically abandoned — a deeply affecting
              place almost no tourists reach.

              **Cultural note:** Before formal cemeteries existed, the bodies of those
              who could not afford burial rites were left in the
              fields of Sagano. Kobo Daishi and later Honen
              performed memorial services here. The stone figures
              were gathered over centuries — each represents a person
              whose death would otherwise have been forgotten.
    - day:
        title: Nintendo Museum
        time: 2026-06-01
        note: |
          Morning free. Download QR codes from
          check.museum-tickets.nintendo.com/myticket from 2pm on
          May 31. Screenshot both QR codes for offline access.

          Route: Kyoto Station > Ogura Station (Kintetsu Kyoto Line,
          ~15 min) > 10 min walk to the museum.
        items:
        - Download QR codes:
            time: 2pm on May 31
            note: "URL: https://check.museum-tickets.nintendo.com/myticket — screenshot both QR codes, one for each person."

        - Nintendo Museum:
            time: 4:30pm
            priority: must
            duration: 1h
            tags: [museum, experience, design, cultural]
            location:
              name: Nintendo Museum
              lat: 34.9315
              lng: 135.7686
            info:
            - purchase: M0715019526
            - visit: "2026-06-01, 4:30 PM - 5:00 PM (JST)"
            - price: 6,600 yen total (2 adults) — already paid
            - tickets: Sanches Caricati Bruna and Cammarosano de Lima Renan
            note: |
              Arrive on time. Tickets are strictly timed entry.

              A museum of Nintendo's full history in their former Uji
              factory — from the company's origins as a playing card
              maker in 1889 through every console generation, with
              giant interactive versions of classic hardware.

              **Cultural note:** Nintendo was founded in 1889 by Fusajiro Yamauchi
              to make hanafuda (flower cards) — traditional Japanese
              playing cards. The company pivoted to toys in the 1960s,
              to electronic toys in the 1970s (Game and Watch), and
              to home video games in 1983 (Famicom/NES). The Uji
              factory opened in 1969; this museum opened in its
              building in October 2024. Even without gaming knowledge,
              the design thinking behind every era of Nintendo hardware
              — and the Japanese cultural obsession with miniaturisation
              and tactile pleasure — is fascinating.

- train:
    from: Kyoto
    to: Tokyo
    note: Nozomi Shinkansen. ~2h20m. Book via Smart EX.

  # ──────────────────────────────────────────
  # TOKYO — LONG STAY (27 nights)
  # ──────────────────────────────────────────

- Tokyo:
    arrives: 2026-06-06
    departs: 2026-07-03
    duration: 27 nights
    location: Toshima City, Tokyo, Japan
    tags: [city, long-stay, neighbourhoods, rainy-season, food, museums]
    note: |
      The rainy season (tsuyu) covers most of this stay — roughly 40-50%
      chance of rain on any given day, peaking mid-June. It rarely rains
      all day. Mornings are often clear; afternoon showers are most
      common. The humidity (75-90%) is more challenging than the rain.
      Strategy: outdoor sightseeing in mornings before 1pm; museums and
      indoor experiences in afternoons and evenings.

      Buy the Grutto Pass on arrival (2,500 yen). Valid 2 months
      at 107 museums, gardens, and zoos. Essential for this stay.
    stay:
    - Kitten House (Airbnb):
        arrives: 2026-06-06T16:00
        departs: 2026-07-03T10:00
        location:
          address: 5-chome-49-2 Higashiikebukuro, Toshima City, Tokyo 170-0013
          lat: 35.7295
          lng: 139.7185
        info:
        - confirmation: HMQFACNZ3K
        - host: Yume
        - host-phone: +81 80-7282-5592
        - platform: Airbnb
        - price: 1,980.44 EUR — already paid
        - type: Brooklyn-style 2LDK, 3 min from Shin-Otsuka, workspace included
        note: |
          Shin-Otsuka is on the Yurakucho and Marunouchi lines.
          Ikebukuro (one stop) is a major hub with easy access to
          Shibuya, Shinjuku, and central Tokyo. Otsuka is a genuine
          residential neighbourhood — local shotengai, sento, and
          izakayas without tourist pricing.
    activities:

    - plan:
        title: Grutto Pass — buy on arrival
        items:
        - Grutto Pass 2026:
            priority: must
            note: |
              Buy from any participating venue on arrival (2,500 yen).
              With 27 nights and strong cultural interests, the pass
              pays for itself within the first week. Available at
              Tokyo National Museum and Ueno Park venues.

              Valid 2 months at 107 Tokyo museums, gardens, zoos,
              and historic sites — including Tokyo National Museum,
              Ueno Zoo, Shinjuku Gyoen, and dozens of smaller
              museums.

        # ─────────────────────────────────────────
        # NEIGHBOURHOOD WALKS
        # ─────────────────────────────────────────

    - plan:
        title: "Neighbourhood — Shimokitazawa"
        items:
        - Shimokitazawa:
            priority: must
            tags: [neighbourhood, indie, vintage, music, walk]
            location:
              name: Shimokitazawa
              lat: 35.6611
              lng: 139.6680
            note: |
              Tokyo's most creative independent neighbourhood —
              vintage clothing shops, tiny live music venues (jazz,
              folk, punk), second-hand bookshops, independent theatre
              spaces, and exceptional coffee.

              **Cultural note:** Shimokitazawa became a counter-culture hub in the 1980s
              when young people priced out of central Tokyo moved here.
              Over 20 independent theatres operate in this single
              neighbourhood — an extraordinary concentration. The
              Sunday flea market at the old station site runs
              year-round. ~30 min from Shin-Otsuka via Ikebukuro.
    - plan:
        title: "Neighbourhood — Nakameguro and Daikanyama"
        items:
        - Nakameguro canal walk:
            priority: must
            tags: [neighbourhood, canal, walk, food]
            location:
              name: Nakameguro Canal
              lat: 35.6419
              lng: 139.6992
            note: |
              A 1.5km walk along the Meguro River canal under
              overhanging trees — lined with small independent cafes,
              bakeries, boutiques, and restaurants popular with
              Tokyo's creative class.

              **Cultural note:** The canal was constructed in the Meiji era for flood
              control. The transformation of its banks into Tokyo's
              most desirable strolling district happened gradually
              from the 1990s onward. In June the leaves are dense
              and green — a lush, quiet urban walk.
        - Daikanyama T-Site Tsutaya:
            note: |
              The adjacent Anjin bar (vintage magazines, cocktails) is excellent in the evening.

              A flagship bookshop in a wooded campus — art books,
              vinyl records, design objects, and magazines from
              around the world. Designed by Klein Dytham Architecture.


    - plan:
        title: "Neighbourhood — Kagurazaka"
        items:
        - Kagurazaka:
            priority: must
            tags: [neighbourhood, Franco-Japanese, food, cultural, walk]
            location:
              name: Kagurazaka
              lat: 35.7010
              lng: 139.7417
            note: |
              A neighbourhood with a genuine Franco-Japanese character
              — French bakeries and bistros alongside traditional
              geisha teahouses, with a famous cobblestone hidden alley
              (Hyogo-yokocho) lined with old wooden buildings.

              **Cultural note:** Kagurazaka was one of Tokyo's most prominent geisha
              districts in the Meiji and Taisho eras — many old ochaya
              still operate behind discreet facades. The French
              community began settling here after the French school
              opened nearby in the 1960s, creating an unintentional
              blend that now feels organic. The only neighbourhood
              in Tokyo where you can eat a perfect croissant in the
              shadow of a centuries-old geisha house.
    - plan:
        title: "Neighbourhood — Koenji"
        items:
        - Koenji:
            tags: [neighbourhood, alternative, vintage, records, walk]
            location:
              name: Koenji
              lat: 35.7057
              lng: 139.6490
            note: |
              Tokyo's alternative neighbourhood — the best place for
              vintage clothing and record hunting, with a strong punk
              and rock music culture and an independent-minded
              community unlike any other part of the city.

              **Cultural note:** Koenji is famous for its Awa Odori dance festival
              (August) and for producing a disproportionate number
              of Japan's independent musicians and artists. The
              shotengai still functions as a genuine local market.
              The vintage shops here are different from Harajuku's
              tourist-facing ones — these are for people who know
              what they are looking for.
    - plan:
        title: "Neighbourhood — Yanaka revisited"
        items:
        - Yanaka in depth:
            tags: [neighbourhood, historical, walk, local]
            note: |
              Return to the neighbourhood from Week 1 — this time
              slower, finding the shops you missed, drinking coffee
              at Kayaba Coffee (a preserved 1938 coffee house),
              walking the cemetery at a different time of day.

              **Cultural note:** Kayaba Coffee (est. 1938) is one of Tokyo's last
              surviving Showa-era coffee houses — wooden interior,
              egg sandwiches, blend coffee, completely unchanged.
              In the evening, the Yanaka Beer Hall (former public
              bath building converted to craft beer bar) is an
              excellent local spot.
        - Nezu Shrine hydrangeas (mid-June):
            tags: [shrine, garden, seasonal]
            note: |
              Nezu Shrine's hill transforms in mid-June — thousands
              of hydrangea plants on the hillside behind the torii
              tunnel. A completely different and extraordinary
              experience from the May visit.
    - plan:
        title: "Museum cluster — Roppongi"
        note: Mori Art Museum, 21_21 Design Sight, and the National Art Center are all within 15 minutes' walk in 
          Roppongi Midtown. A full day of contemporary art and design.
        items:
        - Mori Art Museum and Tokyo City View:
            priority: must
            tags: [museum, contemporary art, viewpoint]
            location:
              name: Mori Art Museum, Roppongi Hills
              lat: 35.6604
              lng: 139.7292
            note: |
              Go in the evening — the Tokyo night view from the City View rooftop is among the best in the city.

              One of Asia's finest contemporary art museums on the
              53rd floor of Roppongi Hills Mori Tower — the ticket
              also covers Tokyo City View (rooftop deck with 360°
              views, best at night).

              **Cultural note:** Founded by developer Minoru Mori (1934-2012), who
              insisted on putting the city's highest cultural
              institution at the top of his commercial tower — the
              idea that art should occupy the highest point, with
              commerce below, was a deliberate statement about values.
              The collection focuses on Asia-Pacific contemporary
              art in ways Western institutions do not.


        - 21_21 Design Sight:
            tags: [museum, design, culture]
            location:
              name: 21_21 Design Sight, Midtown Roppongi
              lat: 35.6655
              lng: 139.7305
            note: |
              A small, exceptionally curated design museum in a
              Tadao Ando building, with rotating exhibitions on
              design, craft, and everyday objects.

              **Cultural note:** The name comes from the concept of seeing beyond perfect
              20/20 vision to a more acute awareness of everyday
              design. The building's folded steel roof is a single
              piece of steel bent to cover the entire space — itself
              a design object. Ando placed most of the museum below
              grade, with only the roof visible from the park.
    - plan:
        title: "Museum — Tokyo National Museum (full return)"
        note: |
          Return for what was missed on May 7 — the Heiseikan and
          a slower look at the Horyuji Treasures. Use the Grutto Pass.
        items:
        - Heiseikan (Japanese Archaeology):
            priority: must
            tags: [museum, history, archaeology]
            note: |
              The permanent archaeology gallery tracing Japan from
              the Jomon period (14,000 BCE) through the Nara period
              — including the famous Jomon dogu (clay figurines) and
              Yayoi bronze ritual objects.

              **Cultural note:** The Jomon period (14,000-300 BCE) produced the world's
              oldest known pottery — Japan's oldest cultural
              contribution to global history. The dogu figurines
              (bizarre goggle-eyed clay figures) remain completely
              mysterious; their purpose is unknown but they appear
              to represent a cosmology with no surviving documentation.
    - plan:
        title: "Museum — Edo-Tokyo Museum (Ryogoku)"
        note: Recently renovated. Near the Kokugikan sumo arena — combine with a sumo district walk.
        items:
        - Edo-Tokyo Museum:
            priority: must
            tags: [museum, history, Tokyo]
            location:
              name: Edo-Tokyo Museum
              lat: 35.6966
              lng: 139.7965
            note: |
              A museum tracing Tokyo's transformation from a small
              fishing village (Edo) to a world capital over 400 years
              — with full-scale reproductions of Nihonbashi Bridge,
              an Edo-period merchant district, and a recreated 1923
              earthquake aftermath.

              **Cultural note:** The museum tells the story of a city destroyed and
              rebuilt multiple times — the 1657 Meireki fire (100,000
              dead), the 1923 Great Kanto earthquake (140,000 dead),
              the 1945 firebombing (80,000+ dead in a single night).
              Each time, Tokyo rebuilt in a new form. The current
              city is its fourth major iteration.
    - plan:
        title: "Museum — Ghibli Museum"
        note: |
          TICKET BOOKING IS URGENT.

          Tickets go on sale the 10th of each month at 10:00 AM JST
          for the following month, via Lawson Ticket (l-tike.com/ghibli).
          In Japan, buy at any Lawson Loppi machine — no Japanese phone
          number required, payment by credit card.

          For a June visit: buy at a Lawson Loppi on May 10 at 10am JST.
          For a July visit: buy at any Lawson in Japan on June 10 at 10am JST.

          Set a phone reminder for both dates. Weekday visits are
          easier to book than weekends. The museum is in Mitaka —
          ~35 min from Shin-Otsuka (Ikebukuro > Mitaka Station, then
          loop bus or 20-min walk through Inokashira Park).
        items:
        - Ghibli Museum, Mitaka:
            priority: must
            duration: 2h
            tags: [museum, design, art, experience]
            location:
              name: Ghibli Museum
              lat: 35.6963
              lng: 139.5705
            note: |
              No tickets sold at the door under any circumstances.

              A small museum designed by Hayao Miyazaki himself —
              no fixed path, hidden staircases, unexpected rooms,
              a film theatre showing exclusive short films, and a
              rooftop garden with the robot soldier from Laputa.
              Entry 1,000 yen per adult.

              **Cultural note:** Miyazaki designed the museum with the motto "Let's
              lose our way together." Every gutter, door handle,
              and window latch was personally designed by him.
              No photography is permitted inside — the museum was
              designed for presence and repeat visits. Returning
              visitors find rooms they missed the first time.
              Each ticket includes one screening of an exclusive
              Ghibli short film not available anywhere else.


    - plan:
        title: "Museum — teamLab Borderless (Azabudai Hills)"
        note: Book tickets well in advance at teamlab.art. Different from Planets — larger, more maze-like. Art reacts 
          to your presence differently.
        items:
        - teamLab Borderless:
            priority: maybe
            tags: [art, immersive, experience]
            location:
              name: teamLab Borderless, Azabudai Hills
              lat: 35.6564
              lng: 139.7430
            note: |
              A vast maze of interconnected art environments where
              digital artworks bleed through walls, floors, and
              ceilings — you wander freely, art changes as you move.

              **Cultural note:** While teamLab Planets (experienced in Week 1) is
              curated and sequential, Borderless is deliberately
              disorienting — you cannot see the full museum because
              it has no fixed shape. The art exists in a continuous
              state that responds to every visitor. The Japanese
              concept of "en" (connection) underlies all of
              teamLab's work.
    - plan:
        title: "Sumo morning practice"
        note: |
          Arrange through your Airbnb host Yume or a specialist
          service (Tokyo Sumo Tours or similar). Practice (keiko) runs
          6-10am daily at stables near Ryogoku. Small groups observe
          in strict silence. Book weeks in advance. This is real
          professional training, not a performance.
        items:
        - Sumo stable morning practice (keiko):
            priority: must
            duration: 2h
            tags: [cultural, sport, Shinto, experience]
            location:
              name: Ryogoku, Tokyo
              lat: 35.6961
              lng: 139.7928
            note: |
              Observe sumo wrestlers (rikishi) in morning training
              — repeating basic techniques thousands of times in
              silence, under the instruction of a former champion.

              **Cultural note:** Sumo is one of Japan's oldest Shinto ritual sports
              — wrestlers are considered sacred vessels during a
              bout, and the ring (dohyo) is purified with salt before
              each match. The rank system (yokozuna at the summit)
              has been maintained for 300 years. A yokozuna may
              practice the same foot-stomp (shiko) 10,000 times
              before a tournament. Observing it in a working stable,
              with the wrestlers feet from you, is one of Tokyo's
              most authentic experiences.
    - plan:
        title: "Kabuki at Kabukiza Theatre"
        note: |
          Kabukiza Theatre is in Ginza, 30 min from Shin-Otsuka.
          Single-act tickets (hitomaku-mi, available at the box office
          on the day, 1,000-3,000 yen) are the right entry point —
          a full programme is 4-5 hours. English synopsis sheets
          available. Check the June programme at shochiku.co.jp.
        items:
        - Kabuki performance:
            priority: must
            duration: 1h30m
            tags: [theatre, cultural, art, traditional]
            location:
              name: Kabukiza Theatre, Ginza
              lat: 35.6697
              lng: 139.7648
            note: |
              Japan's great theatrical art form — an all-male
              performance tradition combining drama, dance, music,
              and extraordinary costume and makeup in plays drawn
              from Japanese history and legend.

              **Cultural note:** Kabuki was founded by Izumo no Okuni, a woman, in
              1603. The Tokugawa government banned women from
              performing in 1629, leading to the development of
              onnagata — male actors specialising in female roles,
              considered among the art form's supreme practitioners.
              The tradition of calling out the actor's family name
              during a performance (kakegoe) is an ancient form of
              audience participation. The Kabukiza Theatre (rebuilt
              2013) was designed by Kengo Kuma.
    - plan:
        title: "Oedo Antique Market"
        note: |
          Held the first and third Sunday of each month at Tokyo
          International Forum (near Yurakucho Station). 9am-4pm. Free.

          June 2026 dates: June 7 and June 21.
          July 2026 date: July 5.
        items:
        - Oedo Antique Market:
            priority: must
            tags: [market, antiques, cultural, shopping]
            location:
              name: Tokyo International Forum, Marunouchi
              lat: 35.6765
              lng: 139.7634
            note: |
              Over 200 vendors selling antique ceramics, Edo-period
              woodblock prints, lacquerware, bronze, textiles, folk
              craft, and curios — one of the largest and finest
              antique markets in Asia.

              **Cultural note:** The market draws professional dealers and collectors
              from across Japan. Unlike tourist souvenir markets,
              everything here was made for a specific Japanese context
              — a sake cup from the 1850s, a Buddhist household altar
              piece, an Edo-period ukiyo-e print. Haggling is accepted
              but must be done respectfully. Bring cash.
    - plan:
        title: "Day trip — Kamakura"
        note: |
          1 hour from Shinjuku by JR Shonan-Shinjuku Line to Kamakura
          (~920 yen each). Go on a weekday.
        items:
        - Kotoku-in Great Buddha:
            priority: must
            tags: [history, landmark, sculpture]
            location:
              name: Kotoku-in, Kamakura
              lat: 35.3167
              lng: 139.5356
            note: |
              A 13.35-metre hollow bronze Amida Buddha seated
              outdoors in a forested valley — Japan's second-largest
              Buddha and most iconic image of medieval Japan.

              **Cultural note:** Cast in 1252 by sculptor Ono Goroemon. Originally
              housed in a large wooden hall; the hall was destroyed
              by a typhoon in 1334 and never rebuilt. The Buddha
              has sat in the open air for 700 years. You can enter
              the statue through doors in its back — inside, rivets
              the size of fists hold it together. Entry 300 yen;
              20 yen extra to enter the statue.
        - Hokoku-ji (Bamboo Temple):
            priority: must
            tags: [temple, garden, bamboo, cultural]
            location:
              name: Hokoku-ji Temple
              lat: 35.3235
              lng: 139.5617
            note: |
              A Zen temple with a private grove of 2,000 bamboo
              stalks — a small, hushed garden where matcha is served
              under the canopy.

              **Cultural note:** Founded 1334. The bamboo grove has been tended for
              nearly 700 years. The matcha pavilion inside the grove
              (500 yen including entry) is one of the most quietly
              beautiful tea experiences available outside Kyoto
              — the bamboo filters the light into something entirely
              green and still.
        - Zen temples near Kita-Kamakura:
            tags: [temple, Zen, cultural]
            note: |
              Get off one stop before Kamakura at Kita-Kamakura.
              Engaku-ji (1282 AD, one of Japan's great Zen monasteries)
              and Kencho-ji (1253 AD, Japan's first Zen training
              monastery) are both 5 minutes' walk from the station.

        - Yuigahama Beach walk:
            time: late afternoon
            tags: [nature, walk, beach]
            note: End the day at the beach — Kamakura's Pacific coastline with mountains rising behind it is a beautiful
              last view before the train home.

    - plan:
        title: "Day trip — Nikko"
        note: |
          2 hours from Ueno by Tobu Nikko Line (direct express,
          1,390 yen each). Purchase the Tobu Nikko All Area Pass for
          unlimited local transport. Go on a weekday. Arrive by 10am.
        items:
        - Tosho-gu Shrine complex:
            priority: must
            tags: [shrine, UNESCO, history, architecture]
            location:
              name: Nikko Tosho-gu
              lat: 36.7581
              lng: 139.5989
            note: |
              The most ornately decorated shrine complex in Japan
              — a UNESCO World Heritage site covering 50+ structures
              over a forested mountainside, built to deify the first
              Tokugawa shogun. Entry 1,300 yen.

              **Cultural note:** Built 1617-1636 to deify Tokugawa Ieyasu (1543-1616),
              the general who reunified Japan after a century of civil
              war. The see-no-evil, hear-no-evil, speak-no-evil carved
              monkeys (Sanzaru) above the stable are the original —
              carved 1636, the earliest known representation of this
              concept in Japan. The Yomeimon Gate contains one pillar
              carved upside down — an intentional structural flaw,
              because only the gods may create something perfect.
        - Kegon Falls:
            tags: [nature, waterfall]
            note: |
              Take the elevator (570 yen) for the observation platform at the base.

              A 97-metre waterfall dropping from Lake Chuzenji into
              the Daiya River valley — one of Japan's three great
              waterfalls.


    - plan:
        title: "Day trip — Kawagoe (Little Edo)"
        note: 40 min from Ikebukuro by Tobu Tojo Line (~480 yen each).
        items:
        - Kawagoe historic district:
            priority: maybe
            tags: [history, cultural, walk, food]
            location:
              name: Kawagoe, Saitama
              lat: 35.9252
              lng: 139.4856
            note: |
              A small city preserving its Edo-period clay-walled
              kura (storehouse) streetscape — often called "Little
              Edo" for the preserved merchant district at its centre.

              **Cultural note:** Kawagoe's kura survived countless fires because their
              thick plaster-coated earthen walls resisted flame. The
              current streetscape dates primarily to the 1890s, when
              merchants rebuilt after the 1893 great fire in the same
              style. Famous for sweet potato (imo) products — snacks,
              soft-serve, shochu — and for the bell tower (Toki-no-Kane)
              that has rung the hours since 1624.
    - plan:
        title: "Day trip — Yokohama"
        note: 30 min from Shinjuku by Shonan-Shinjuku Line (~680 yen each).
        items:
        - Yokohama Chinatown:
            tags: [food, cultural, neighbourhood]
            location:
              name: Yokohama Chinatown
              lat: 35.4419
              lng: 139.6449
            note: |
              Excellent for roast meat (char siu), dumplings, and steamed buns — none of which involve seafood.

              Japan's largest Chinatown — 500+ restaurants and shops
              in a dense grid centring on the Kanteibyo temple.


        - Sankeien Garden:
            priority: must
            tags: [garden, history, architecture]
            location:
              name: Sankeien Garden
              lat: 35.4139
              lng: 139.6336
            note: |
              A vast landscape garden preserving 10 historical
              buildings transplanted from across Japan — a three-story
              pagoda from Kyoto (1457), a farmhouse from Shirakawa-go,
              a tea ceremony villa from Kii Province.

              **Cultural note:** Created by silk merchant Hara Sankei (1868-1939) between
              1906 and 1928. Sankei bought and moved endangered
              historical structures from across the country before they
              were demolished — an intentional act of conservation
              rather than a surviving accident.
    - plan:
        title: "Day trip — Kawaguchiko / Mount Fuji (weather-dependent)"
        note: |
          2 hours from Shinjuku by express bus (direct to Kawaguchiko,
          2,000 yen each way — book at Shinjuku Expressway Bus Terminal).

          ONLY GO IF MOUNT FUJI IS VISIBLE. Check fuji-san.info the
          day before and the morning of the planned visit. During the
          rainy season (June-mid July), Fuji is frequently obscured.
          The day trip is not worth making for the lake alone.
        items:
        - Lake Kawaguchi and Fuji Panorama Ropeway:
            tags: [nature, Mount Fuji, viewpoint]
            note: |
              Lake Kawaguchi is the most accessible of the five Fuji
              lakes — the ropeway from Kachikachi-yama gives elevated
              views of the lake with Fuji rising behind it.

              **Cultural note:** Mount Fuji (3,776m) is Japan's highest mountain and
              an active stratovolcano — last erupted in 1707. It is
              sacred to the Shinto faith and has been climbed by
              pilgrims since the 12th century. Its perfectly conical
              shape — the result of a single eruptive vent — is its
              aesthetic signature. Hokusai's 36 Views of Mount Fuji
              (1831) established it as a global icon. Viewing it
              clearly from the Five Lakes area, reflected in still
              water, is one of Japan's most affecting sights.
    - plan:
        title: "Local rhythms — living in Otsuka"
        items:
        - Weekly sento visits:
            priority: must
            tags: [local, cultural, relax, neighbourhood]
            note: |
              A neighbourhood public bath (sento) charges ~500 yen
              and is a community institution — residents of all ages
              bathe together in shared pools of hot water, in a
              ritual of daily washing that has anchored Japanese
              neighbourhood life for centuries.

              **Cultural note:** The sento is distinct from onsen (mineral spring water)
              — it is simply a neighbourhood bath, heated municipal
              water, where people go because their apartment has a
              small bathroom and the sento has a proper deep tub.
              In a city where apartment living compresses life, the
              sento is one of the last genuinely communal spaces.
              Ask Yume (host) for the nearest one.
        - Toden Arakawa tram ride:
            tags: [local, transport, experience]
            location:
              name: Otsuka Station — Toden Arakawa Line
              lat: 35.7349
              lng: 139.7285
            note: |
              Tokyo's last surviving streetcar line, running from
              Otsuka through residential neighbourhoods to Waseda
              and Minowabashi — 30km of old Tokyo visible from
              a tram window.

              **Cultural note:** The Toden Arakawa Line (now officially the Tokyo Sakura
              Tram) opened 1911 and is the only surviving remnant
              of the extensive tram network that covered Tokyo before
              the 1964 Olympics, when most lines were removed to ease
              road traffic. Ride it end to end on a slow afternoon
              — 170 yen flat fare, about 1 hour.
        - Otsuka shotengai and local izakayas:
            tags: [local, food, neighbourhood]
            note: |
              The covered shopping street around Otsuka Station has
              local butchers, vegetable shops, and a fishmonger.
              The izakayas in Otsuka and Sugamo are priced for
              residents, not tourists. Find one by wandering rather
              than researching — the best ones have hand-written menus
              and no English signage.

        - Depachika circuit — Isetan Shinjuku:
            priority: must
            tags: [food, cultural, experience]
            note: |
              Return visits to the B1-B2 floors of Isetan in Shinjuku
              — Japan's finest department store food halls, with
              prepared foods, wagashi, sake, and seasonal specialities.

              **Cultural note:** Each depachika has a completely different personality.
              Also worth trying Matsuya Ginza and Mitsukoshi Nihonbashi
              for different curatorial perspectives. The Isetan B1
              wagashi counter alone is worth a dedicated visit.
